{"title_page": "Sichuan anti-Mongol fortresses", "text_new": "{{short description|Defensive fortresses in the Southern Song dynasty}}\n[[File:Fishingtown.jpg|right|thumb|333x333px|A ladder towards [[Diaoyucheng]] (Fishingtown), part of the 48 fortresses that defended [[Southern Song]] from the [[Mongol Empire]]]]\nThe '''Sichuan anti-Mongol fortresses''' are 83<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://kknews.cc/history/b52lg5j.html|title=\u5d16\u5c71\u4e4b\u5f8c\uff0c\u9084\u6709\u51cc\u9704\uff01\u5357\u5b8b\u51cc\u9704\u57ce\u9577\u5be7\u8ecd\u625b\u8d77\u4e86\u5b8b\u4eba\u6700\u5f8c\u7684\u6230\u65d7|language=zh-hk|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> mountain cities built by the soldiers and civilians of the [[Southern Song dynasty|Southern Song Dynasty]] during the [[Mongol conquest of China]] in [[Sichuan]] to fight against the invasion of the [[Mongol Empire]]. Taking full advantage of the geographical advantages of the [[Sichuan Basin]],<ref name=\"\u56db\u5ddd\u76c6\u5730\u7684\u5357\u5b8b\u57ce\u5821\">{{Cite journal|last=\u8303\u6653|year=2007\u5e74|title=\u56db\u5ddd\u76c6\u5730\u7684\u5357\u5b8b\u57ce\u5821\u2014\u2014\u7ea2\u5c42\u65b9\u5c71\u4e0a\u5931\u843d\u7684\u53e4\u57ce\u8981\u585e\u7fa4|journal=\u4e2d\u56fd\u56fd\u5bb6\u5730\u7406|issue=\u7b2c9\u671f}}</ref> they formed a comprehensive three-dimensional defense system, which succeeded in resisting the Mongol attacks for up to 53 years, greatly extending the life of Southern Song. They also made Sichuan the last to be conquered by the Mongolians in 1288.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"\u5b8b\u8499\uff08\u5143\uff09\u6218\u4e89\u65f6\u671f\u56db\u5ddd\u519b\u4e8b\u5730\u7406\u521d\u6b65\u7814\u7a76\">{{Cite journal|last=\u8d75\u5c14\u9633|year=2014\u5e74|title=\u5b8b\u8499\uff08\u5143\uff09\u6218\u4e89\u65f6\u671f\u56db\u5ddd\u519b\u4e8b\u5730\u7406\u521d\u6b65\u7814\u7a76|journal=\u897f\u5357\u5927\u5b66}}</ref> Due to the defense of the fortresses, it was difficult to settle the Sichuan region. The Mongol Army had to abort its original strategy of \"taking Shu (Sichuan) and destroying [[Song dynasty|Song]]\" and moved to the area of [[Jingzhou]] and [[Xiangyang]] starting from 1271, defeating the Song Dynasty via the [[Han River (Hubei)|Han River]].<ref name=\"\u5b8b\u5143\u6218\u4e89\u4e2d\u56db\u5ddd\u7684\u5b8b\u519b\u5c71\u57ce\u53ca\u5176\u73b0\u72b6\">{{Cite journal|last=\u859b\u7389\u6811|year=1993\u5e74|title=\u5b8b\u5143\u6218\u4e89\u4e2d\u56db\u5ddd\u7684\u5b8b\u519b\u5c71\u57ce\u53ca\u5176\u73b0\u72b6|journal=\u56db\u5ddd\u6587\u7269|issue=\u7b2c1\u671f}}</ref> Among the fortresses, [[Diaoyucheng]] was the most famous as the death place of [[M\u00f6ngke Khan]], allegedly because of either [[dysentery]] or injuries from attacking the fortress.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.guoxue123.com/other/jq/yuan/063.htm|title=\u5e1d\u56fd\u7684\u6781\u76db\uff1a\u8499\u54e5\u6c57\u65f6\u671f\uff0c1251\u20141259\u5e74_\u5251\u6865\u4e2d\u56fd\u8fbd\u897f\u590f\u91d1\u5143\u53f2_\u56fd\u5b66\u5bfc\u822a|website=www.guoxue123.com|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nAt present, there are still 48 fortresses kept to this date from the Song Dynasty in [[Sichuan]] and [[Chongqing]]. Among them, five of them (including [[Diaoyucheng]] and [[Baidicheng]]) were included as [[Major Historical and Cultural Site Protected at the National Level|Major Historical and Cultural Sites Protected at the National Level]]. Another 14 of the fortresses were selected as [[major historical and cultural sites protected by Sichuan Province]] and [[Major historical and cultural sites protected by Chongqing City|Chongqing]]. But overall, except for a select few such as Diaoyucheng, most of them have not been effectively protected and developed.<ref>{{Cite news|last=\u6731\u96ea\u9ece|first=|url=http://www.sc.gov.cn/10462/10464/11716/11718/2014/5/23/10302683.shtml|title=30\u5ea7\u5b8b\u5143\u53e4\u57ce\u85cf\u5728\u5df4\u5c71\u8700\u6c34\u95f4|date=23 May 2014|work=\u56db\u5ddd\u65e5\u62a5|access-date=2014-12-31|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe [[Mongol conquest of Song China|Sino-Mongol wars]] in Sichuan began in 1227, known as the 1227 incident or the Dinghai incident. The Mongolian army attacked [[Western Xia]] while sending troops into Sichuan, and captured five prefectures belonging to [[Lizhou Circuit]] near Sichuan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kknews.cc/history/5z99266.html|title=\u6539\u8b8a\u6b77\u53f2\u7684\u4e00\u6230\uff0c\u5b8b\u8499\u91e3\u9b5a\u57ce\u4e4b\u6230\u7cfb\u5217\u59cb\u672b1\u2014\u2014\u5e8f\u7ae0|language=zh-tw|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> In 1236, [[Kashin (general)|Kashin]], the second son of [[\u00d6gedei Khan]], led the Mongolian army to the south of Sichuan, breaking through the Song defense line at Kaizhou, Lizhou Circuit, and entered the [[Sichuan Basin]]. Three circuits in Sichuan were almost completely occupied except [[Kuizhou Circuit]], and Song only kept a few states such as [[Luzhou]], [[Gu\u01d2 Prefecture|Guo prefecture]], and [[Hezhou (Chongqing)|Hezhou]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=\u8131\u8131\u7b49|title=\u300a\u5b8b\u53f2\u00b7\u5217\u4f20\u7b2c\u4e8c\u767e\u516b\u00b7\u5fe0\u4e49\u56db\u00b7\u66f9\u53cb\u95fb\u4f20\u300b}}</ref>\u3002Since then, the Mongolian army has continued to invade Sichuan. In 1241, it took [[Chengdu]] again, nearing [[Kuizhou]], and the Sichuan defense line was nearly destroyed. In 1241, Yu Jie moved the military and political center of Sichuan from Chengdu to Chongqing, which was easier to defend. After understanding that defending on flat land failed to stop the Mongol army, Yu began to build a mountain defense system and relocated the state government offices in the Sichuan province into the [[Daba Mountains]].<ref name=\"\u5b8b\u5143\u6218\u4e89\u4e2d\u56db\u5ddd\u7684\u5b8b\u519b\u5c71\u57ce\u53ca\u5176\u73b0\u72b6\"/> Most of the fortresses were located near cliffs of the mountains. The top of the mountains were wide and flat, there was enough [[arable land]] and water, so they were self-sufficient and could be defended for a long time. At the same time, the mountain cities were often connected by rivers and roads at the junction of valleys or rivers. The defense of the Southern Song Dynasty used [[Chongqing]], [[Jiading]] and [[Kuizhou|Kuimen]] as the centers of the defense of Sichuan, which resisted the invasion of Mongolia for 53 years. Even after the [[Battle of Yamen]] in 1279, which ended the [[Southern Song dynasty]], two of the fortresses (Santaicheng and Lingxiaocheng) had not fallen. The former lasted for an extra year until 1280, and the latter lasted until 1288, making it the last place under Song control.\n\n== List ==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Name\n!Year of construction\n!Year of downfall\n!Original [[Circuit (administrative division)|Circuit]]\n!Original [[Zhou (country subdivision)|Zhou]] or [[Fu (country subdivision)|Fu]]\n!Current location\n!Protection level\n!Image\n|-\n|Sanguicheng\n|1243\n|1275\n|[[Chengdufu Circuit|Chengdufu]]\n|[[Jiading Fu]]\n|[[Shizhong District, Leshan|Shizhong District]], [[Leshan]]\n|protected by Leshan\n|\n|-\n|Jiudingcheng\n|1243\n|1275\n|[[Chengdufu Circuit|Chengdufu]]\n|[[Jiading Fu]]\n|Shizhong District, Leshan\n|protected by Leshan\n| style=\"padding:0\" |[[File:Artillery_Battery_of_Jiuding_Fortress.jpg|link=https://zh.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Artillery_Battery_of_Jiuding_Fortress.jpg|125x125px]]\n|-\n|Ziyuncheng\n|1243\n|1275\n|[[Chengdufu Circuit|Chengdufu]]\n|[[Jiading Fu]]\n|[[Qianwei County]], Leshan\n|\n|\n|-\n|Qingxicheng\n|\n|\n|[[Chengdufu Circuit|Chengdufu]]\n|[[Jiading Fu]]\n|[[Muchuan County]], Leshan\n|\n|\n|-\n|Baiyanzhai\n|\n|\n|[[Chengdufu Circuit|Chengdufu]]\n|[[Jiading Fu]]\n|Muchuan County, Leshan\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Diaoyucheng]]\n|1240\n|1279\n|[[Tongchuanfu Circuit|Tongchuanfu]]\n|[[Hezhou (Chongqing)|Hezhou]]\n|[[Hechuan District]], [[Chongqing]]\n|[[Major Historical and Cultural Site Protected at the National Level|protected at the national level]]\n| styl