{"title_page": "Pretty Much Dead Already", "text_new": "{{Good article}}\n{{Infobox television episode\n|title=Pretty Much Dead Already\n|series=[[The Walking Dead (TV series)|The Walking Dead]]\n|image= PrettyMuchDeadAlreadyWD.jpg\n|caption=[[Rick Grimes|Rick]] tries to convince [[Hershel Greene|Hershel]] to let his group of survivors stay at his ranch.\n|season=2\n|episode=7\n|airdate={{Start date|2011|11|27}}\n|writer=[[Scott M. Gimple]]\n|director=[[Michelle MacLaren]]\n|guests=*[[IronE Singleton]] as [[T-Dog (The Walking Dead)|Theodore \"T-Dog\" Douglas]]\n*[[Madison Lintz]] as [[Sophia Peletier]]\n*[[Lauren Cohan]] as [[Maggie Greene]]\n*[[Emily Kinney]] as [[Beth Greene]]\n*[[Scott Wilson (actor)|Scott Wilson]] as [[Hershel Greene]]\n*[[Jane McNeill]] as Patricia\n*[[James Allen McCune]] as Jimmy\n| season_article = The Walking Dead (season 2)\n| episode_list = List of The Walking Dead episodes\n|prev=[[Secrets (The Walking Dead)|Secrets]]\n|next=[[Nebraska (The Walking Dead)|Nebraska]]\n}}\n\n\"'''Pretty Much Dead Already'''\" is the seventh episode and mid-season finale of the [[The Walking Dead (season 2)|second season]] of the [[Apocalyptic and post-apocalyptic fiction|post-apocalyptic]] [[Horror fiction|horror]] [[television series]] ''[[The Walking Dead (TV series)|The Walking Dead]]''. It originally aired on [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]] in the United States on November 27, 2011. In the episode, Glenn ([[Steven Yeun]]) reveals to the group that there are walkers in the Greenes' barn, dividing the group on what to do. Hershel Greene ([[Scott Wilson (actor)|Scott Wilson]]) sets a deadline for the group to leave, unless [[Rick Grimes]] ([[Andrew Lincoln]]) does a difficult task. Meanwhile, [[Shane Walsh (The Walking Dead)|Shane Walsh]] ([[Jon Bernthal]]) slowly loses his sanity after many secrets around him are revealed and [[Carol Peletier]] begins to question whether her daughter, [[Sophia Peletier|Sophia]] will be found.\n\nThe episode was written by [[Scott M. Gimple]] and directed by [[Michelle MacLaren]]. The death of Sophia Peletier is a prominent theme in \"Pretty Much Dead Already\"; she was killed by Grimes following her conversion into a walker. [[Robert Kirkman]] felt that killing Sophia off would add more dimension to the show, and create more flexibility in regards to the progression of the storylines, as well as leading to very different storylines from the [[The Walking Dead (comic book)|comic series]], with Carol outliving her daughter, as opposed to the other way around. \"Pretty Much Dead Already\" generated acclaim from critics, who praised the episode's conclusion and the development of the characters. Upon airing in the United States, the episode attained 6.62 million viewers and a 3.5 rating in the 18-49 demographic, according to [[Nielsen ratings]]. It became the highest-rated cable telecast of the day, as well as the fourth most-viewed cable program of the week.\n\n==Plot==\nGlenn ([[Steven Yeun]]), at the urging of Dale ([[Jeffrey DeMunn]]), finally tells the group that the Greene family's barn is full of [[zombie|walkers]]. The group inspects the barn, and Shane ([[Jon Bernthal]]) believes they should clear the barn, but [[Rick Grimes|Rick]] ([[Andrew Lincoln]]) believes they need to get Hershel ([[Scott Wilson (actor)|Scott Wilson]])'s blessing since they are still guests on his property. Shane criticizes Rick for continuing the seemingly pointless search for Carol ([[Melissa McBride]])'s daughter Sophia, infuriating Daryl ([[Norman Reedus]]).\n\nLater, Maggie Greene ([[Lauren Cohan]]) confronts Glenn about revealing the barn's secret to the group, but Glenn says his personal well-being is more important than her affections. Carol tries to stop Daryl from searching for Sophia alone, but he later comes back to show her another [[Rosa laevigata|Cherokee rose]] blooming, helping to restore Carol's faith they will find Sophia. Elsewhere, Rick confronts Shane about his defiant attitude. The two argue until Rick exclaims that Lori ([[Sarah Wayne Callies]]) is pregnant. As Rick leaves, Shane congratulates him, but is shocked and scared by this revelation.\n\nRick approaches Hershel about the walkers in the barn, but Hershel refuses to allow them to harm the walkers. He, Maggie, and [[Jimmy (The Walking Dead)|Jimmy]] (James Allen McCune) bring Rick to a forest swamp where two walkers are stuck. Hershel insists that if Rick's group is to stay on his farm, they must treat the walkers as people, and shows Rick how to snare and lead the walkers back.\n\nMeanwhile, Shane confronts Lori about her pregnancy, believing himself to be the father. Lori denies this, and Shane storms off, but Carl ([[Chandler Riggs]]) stops him, insisting that they stay and search for Sophia. Dale ([[Jeffrey DeMunn]]), witnessing this, warns Andrea ([[Laurie Holden]]) about Shane's erratic behavior, and then distracts the others long enough to take the weapons from the camp and to hide them in the swamp. Shane discovers the missing weapons and tracks down Dale, demanding he return them. Dale gives in to Shane, but warns him about losing his humanity. Shane replies that they are \"pretty much dead already\".\n\nShane arms the rest of the group and they converge on the barn just as Hershel, Rick, and the others return with the snared walkers. Shane screams that walkers are not people and shoots one of the captive walkers before breaking the locks off the barn doors. Walkers start to file out, and Shane, Andrea, T-Dog ([[IronE Singleton]]), Daryl, and Glenn execute the zombies while the others watch. At the last moment, Sophia ([[Madison Lintz]]) emerges from the barn, dead and zombified. The group is paralyzed with shock and sadness, unable to act as Sophia walks towards them. Only Rick is able to step forward and shoot her.\n\n==Production==\n[[File: Madison Lintz 2014.jpg | thumb | left | 195px | This episode marks the departure of [[Sophia Peletier]], portrayed by [[Madison Lintz]].]]\n{{Quote box |quoted=true |bgcolor=#FFFFF0 |salign=center |width=30% |align=right | quote = Oh yeah, that was her in makeup. That\u2019s the consolation prize to finding out that you're dying on the show. It\u2019s never fun for an actor to learn that they\u2019re being written out of the show and it\u2019s a hard thing to do. It\u2019s something that we never take lightly. But, you know, you\u2019ve got to kill characters! On this show, you at least get the benefit of getting up and coming back as a zombie. That hopefully makes it a little less uncool.|source = '''[[Robert Kirkman]]'''<ref name=ent2/>}}\n\"Pretty Much Dead Already\" was written by [[Scott M. Gimple]] and directed by [[Michelle MacLaren]].<ref name=amc23/> It features recurring appearances from [[Lauren Cohan]], [[Scott Wilson (actor)|Scott Wilson]], [[IronE Singleton]], [[Madison Lintz]], [[Emily Kinney]], [[Jane McNeill]], James Allen McCune, and Amber Chaney.<ref name=amc23>{{cite web|url=http://www.amctv.com/shows/the-walking-dead/episodes/season-2/pretty-much-dead-already|title=Episode 7: Pretty Much Dead Already|publisher=AMC|accessdate=February 26, 2012}}</ref> Following the initial broadcast of the previous installment, \"[[Secrets (The Walking Dead)|Secrets]]\", writer [[Robert Kirkman]] teased the following episode \"Pretty Much Dead Already\". He stated: \"There's a lot of big stuff out there that we will be wrapping up to a certain extent. In the writers' room we were fully aware that we were coming up on this hiatus, so we definitely wrote to it. I think people are going to be a little shocked.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2011/11/21/the-walking-dead-writer-robert-kirkman-secrets/|title='The Walking Dead': Writer Robert Kirkman talks about tonight's episode and teases next week's 'shocking' finale|first=Clark|last=Collis|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time, Inc.]]|date=November 21, 2011|accessdate=January 9, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe death of Sophia Peletier is a major incident in \"Pretty Much Dead Already\", largely affecting the themes of the episode. After the group has shot the walkers housed in Hershel Greene's barn, Sophia appears from the barn as a walker, much to the groups' dismay. A disturbed and distraught Rick Grimes pulls out his weapon and makes the decision to shoot her. Despite being initially surprised about her character's being killed off, Madison Lintz concluded that she understood its aftermath for the show.<ref name=amc>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.amctv.com/the-walking-dead/2012/01/madison-lintz-interview.php|title=Q&A - Madison Lintz (Sophia)|last=Rosenburg|first=Eli|publisher=[[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]]|date=January 2, 2012|accessdate=January 9, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120107201903/http://blogs.amctv.com/the-walking-dead/2012/01/madison-lintz-interview.php|archivedate=January 7, 2012}}</ref> Lintz affirmed that portraying a walker was a welcoming experience for her, and stated that she was \"going to look back on and say that was amazing.\"<ref name=amc/> Robert Kirkman felt that killing Sophia would add more dimension to the show, as well as add more flexibility to its storyline progression. \"When a good idea comes up, you have to go with it,\" he articulated.<ref name=hr/> \"Sophia is a character who is still alive in the comic book series and who has contributed quite a bit to the overall narrative and informed a lot of story lines for a lot of different characters. Having Carol [...] survive her daughter as opposed to the other way around as it is in the comics is going to lead to interesting but different stories.\"<ref name=hr>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/walking-dead-midseason-finale-robert-kirkman-265484|title='The Walking Dead' Dissection: Robert Kirkman Talks Death and What's Ahead|first=Leslie|last=Goldberg|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|date=November 27, 2011|accessdate=January 9, 2012}}</ref> Although Kirkman was not on set during production of the sequence, Gimple retrieved shell casings from the [[blank (cartridge)|blanks]] that were fired on set.<ref name=ent2/> Referred to as \"Barnageddon\" by the writers, Kirkman asserted that he emphasized unpredictability while creating the scene.<ref name=ent2>{{cite web|url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2011/11/28/walking-dead-finale-kirkman-2/|title='Walking Dead' writer Robert Kirkman talks midseason finale shocker|first=Clark|last=Collis|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time, Inc.]]|date=November 28, 2011|accessdate=January 9, 2012}}</ref>\n<blockquote>\nIt's good to know people didn't see it coming. That's a big concern when you have this kind of story line and you are leading to that kind of reveal. You don't want people to be expecting it, especially in the ''Walking Dead''. I pride myself in the fact that, when you pick up an issue of the comic, you don't know what's going to happen at any time. So any time we can work that into the show and maintain that in a television environment, it's very exciting for me. I\u2019m glad people are being caught off guard.<ref name=ent2/>\n</blockquote>\nOther themes prevalent in the episode include Lori's pregnancy. After getting into a heated argument, Rick reveals to Shane about her pregnancy. Although he didn't question who the biological father was, Robert Kirkman felt that Rick was \"smart enough to know that the kid's either his or Shane's and there may not be any way of ever finding out that definitively.\"<ref name=ent2/> He continued: \"Bringing that up to his wife, who he loves, is only going to be painful for her. I think that\u2019s him being a good husband and him showing his tremendous leadership ability in that he can put his self aside for the betterment of someone else.\"<ref name=ent2/>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Ratings===\n\"Pretty Much Dead Already\" was initially broadcast in November 27, 2011 in the United States on AMC. Upon airing, it garnered 6.62 million viewers and a 3.5 rating in the 18-49 demographic, according to [[Nielsen ratings]]. The episode became the highest-rated cable program of the day, obtaining significantly higher ratings than ''[[Kourtney and Kim Take New York]]'' on [[E!]] and ''[[Real Housewives of Atlanta]]'' on [[Bravo (US TV channel)|Bravo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2011/11/29/sunday-cable-ratings-the-walking-dead-goes-out-on-top-kardashians-housewives-soul-train-awards-hell-on-wheels-boardwalk-empire-homeland-dexter-more/112136/|title=Sunday Cable Ratings: 'The Walking Dead' Goes Out on Top + Kardashians, 'Housewives' 'Soul Train Awards,' 'Hell On Wheels,' 'Boardwalk Empire,' 'Homeland,' 'Dexter' & More|publisher=[[TV by the Numbers]]|last=Seidman|first=Robert|date=November 29, 2011|accessdate=November 30, 2011}}</ref> \"Pretty Much Dead Already\" received the show's highest ratings since \"[[Bloodletting (The Walking Dead)|Bloodletting]]\", which obtained 6.7 million viewers and a 3.6 rating in the 18-49 demographic.<ref name=tvratings>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2011/10/25/sunday-cable-ratings-the-walking-dead-slips-still-tops-nj-housewives-boardwalk-empire-homeland-dexter-much-more/108350/|title=Sunday Cable Ratings: 'The Walking Dead' Slips, Still Tops; + NJ Housewives, 'Boardwalk Empire,' 'Homeland,' 'Dexter' & Much More|publisher=[[TV by the Numbers]]|last=Gorman|first=Bill|date=October 25, 2011|accessdate=January 9, 2012}}</ref> In addition, the episode became the fourth highest-rated cable telecast of the week, and the highest-rated non sport cable telecast of the week dated November 27.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2011/11/29/cable-top-25-nfl-football-the-walking-dead-top-weekly-cable-viewing-for-the-week-ending-nov-27-2011/112169/|title=Cable Top 25: NFL Football, 'The Walking Dead' Top Weekly Cable Viewing for the Week Ending Nov 27, 2011|publisher=[[TV by the Numbers]]|last=Seidman|first=Robert|date=November 27, 2011|accessdate=January 9, 2012}}</ref> Total viewership and ratings for the episode significantly increased from the preceding installment, \"[[Secrets (The Walking Dead)|Secrets]]\", which garnered 6.08 million viewers and a 3.1 rating amongst adults in the 18-49 demographic.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2011/11/22/sunday-cable-ratings-the-walking-dead-stays-on-top-nascar-championship-housewives-atl-hell-on-wheels-boardwalk-empire-homeland-dexter-more/111468/|title=Sunday Cable Ratings: 'The Walking Dead' Stays On Top + NASCAR Championship, 'Housewives ATL,' 'Hell On Wheels,' 'Boardwalk Empire,' 'Homeland,' 'Dexter' & More|publisher=[[TV by the Numbers]]|last=Gorman|first=Bill|date=November 22, 2010|accessdate=January 9, 2012}}</ref> In the United Kingdom, \"Pretty Much Dead Already\" received 666,000 viewers, subsequently becoming the most-watched cable program on [[Fox (UK and Ireland)|FX]] of the week dated December 4.<ref>{{cite press|url=http://www.barb.co.uk/whats-new/weekly-top-10? |title=Weekly Top 10 Programmes |publisher=[[Broadcasters' Audience Research Board]] |accessdate=January 9, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140718204656/http://www.barb.co.uk/whats-new/weekly-top-10 |archivedate=July 18, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\n{{Quote box |quoted=true |bgcolor=#FFFFF0 |salign=center |width=30% |align=right | quote = \"Pretty Much Dead Already\" tied up the immediate loose ends, and like Season 1's \"[[TS-19]]\", contained a noisy last five minutes. Your opinion on the episode depends on how engaged you were in the season so far. As soon as the barn doors opened, the events were well executed, albeit foreseeable|source = '''Mark Maurer<br>''The Star Ledger'''''<ref name=str/>}}\n\"Pretty Much Dead Already\" was critically acclaimed by television critics and is generally considered to be one of the best episodes of the series. Eric Goldman of [[IGN]] evaluated the episode as \"completely depressing\", and added that the dark nature made the series excel. Goldman ultimately gave the episode an eight out of ten, signifying a \"great\" rating.<ref name=ign>{{cite web |url=http://tv.ign.com/articles/121/1213275p1.html |title=The Walking Dead: \"Pretty Much Dead Already\" Review |last=Goldman|first=Eric|date=November 27, 2011 |publisher=IGN|accessdate=January 2, 2012}}</ref> Aaron Rutkoff of ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' felt that the episode was the series' best installment.<ref name=\"Rutkoff\">{{cite news|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2011/11/27/the-walking-dead-season-2-episode-7-pretty-much-dead-already-tv-recap/?mod=google_news_blog|title='The Walking Dead,' Season 2, Episode 7, 'Pretty Much Dead Already' Midseason Finale|last=Rutkoff|first=Aaron|date=November 27, 2011|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|accessdate=November 28, 2011}}</ref> Writing for ''[[The Grand Rapids Press]]'', John Serba opined that \"Pretty Much Dead Already\" was a delightful ending to the first portion of the season.<ref name=serba>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlive.com/movies/index.ssf/2011/11/walking_dead_postmortem_pretty.html|title='Walking Dead' postmortem, 'Pretty Much Dead Already': Conclusive arguments about the right to zombie life|first=John|last=Serba|work=[[The Grand Rapids Press]]|publisher=Dan Gaydou|date=November 28, 2011|accessdate=January 10, 2012}}</ref> Zack Handlen of ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' stated that prior to its ending, the episode was \"the usual mix of pretty good and deeply irritating.\"<ref name=av/> Handlen lauded the character development in the installment; \"The episode puts a lot of effort into heightening the tensions between Hershel and Rick's people, and while it\u2019s not exactly subtle, it makes enough sense to be effective. This is conflict that should've been building for a few episodes now, instead of arriving fully formed right before it explodes, but I'm willing to take what I can get.\"<ref name=av>{{cite web|url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/pretty-much-dead-already,65692/|title=Pretty Much Dead Already|last=Handlen|first=Zack|date=November 28, 2011|accessdate=January 10, 2012|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|publisher=[[The Onion]]}}</ref> Concluding his review, he issued the episode an A\u2013 grade.<ref name=av/> [[Digital Spy]]'s Morgan Jeffrey avouched that \"Pretty Much Dead Already\" was \"excellent\", and added that the tension \"slowly ratchets up to an almost unbearable level.\"<ref name=digi>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/s135/the-walking-dead/recaps/a352768/the-walking-dead-pretty-much-dead-already-recap.html|title='The Walking Dead': 'Pretty Much Dead Already' recap|first=Morgan|last=Jeffrey|publisher=[[Digital Spy]]|date=November 28, 2011|accessdate=January 10, 2012}}</ref> Some critics were divided with the episode. ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' journalist Nate Rawlings felt that while the writers put a lot of substance into the characters, many of them are still underdeveloped.<ref name=time/> Gina McIntyre of ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' felt that some parts of the episode lacked cohesion and direction.<ref name=la>{{cite web|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/showtracker/2011/11/walking-dead-recap-pretty-much-dead-already.html|title='The Walking Dead' recap: They shoot zombies, don't they?|first=Gina|last=McIntyre|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]|date=November 28, 2011|accessdate=January 10, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe episode's concluding scene involving Sophia's death was cited as the episode highlight. Janet Turley of ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' asserted that the sequence was \"fiction not afraid to provoke\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/janet-turley/the-walking-dead-midseries-recap_b_1116624.html|title=The Walking Dead Midseries Finale: Pretty Much Dead Already|work=[[Huffington Post]]|publisher=[[Arianna Huffington]]|first=Janet|last=Turley|date=November 28, 2011|accessdate=January 9, 2012}}</ref> while Goldman described it as an \"absolutely horrific scenario\".<ref name=ign/> [[CNN]]'s Henry Hanks opined that the sequence \"left [them] with a final scene that we'll be talking about until then.\"<ref name=\"Hanks\">{{cite news|url=http://marquee.blogs.cnn.com/2011/11/28/things-come-to-a-head-on-the-walking-dead/|title=Things come to a head on 'The Walking Dead'|last=Hanks|first=Henry|date=November 28, 2011|publisher=CNN|accessdate=November 28, 2011}}</ref> ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]''{{'s}} Starlee Kine asserted that it contained cinematic qualities, and felt that the scene was \"satisfying, sad, and fun\".<ref name=\"Kine\">{{cite news|url=http://nymag.com/daily/entertainment/2011/11/walking-dead-the-walking-dead-recap-finders-fee.html|title=The Walking Dead Recap: Finder\u2019s Fee|last=Kine|first=Starlee|date=November 28, 2011|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|publisher=New York Media|accessdate=January 9, 2012}}</ref> She wrote: \"It was everything you've ever wanted this show to be. Zombies plus no dialogue, such a winning combination! And how great was it that Sophia was dead instead of impossibly alive somewhere, holed up with Merle or Morgan or those warmhearted gang members in Atlanta. And because she was granted more screen time than she ever was when she was alive, we were finally able to care about the loss of her short, young life.\"<ref name=\"Kine\"/> Jen Chaney of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' echoed synonymous sentiments; \"Really, the final moments of the last episode before the AMC series' December/January hiatus played like a fireworks finale on the Fourth of July, assuming your Fourth of July celebrations typically involve zombies and a pile of corpses.\"<ref name=wp>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/celebritology/post/walking-dead-in-pretty-much-dead-already-they-shoot-zombies-dont-they/2011/11/27/gIQA5Lai3N_blog.html|title=\u2018Walking Dead\u2019: In \u2018Pretty Much Dead Already,\u2019 they shoot zombies, don\u2019t they?|first=Jen|last=Chenay|work=[[The Washington Post]]|publisher=[[The Washington Post Company]]|date=November 28, 2011|accessdate= January 10, 2012}}</ref> Rawlings concluded that it was the perfect resolution for what he called \"television's slowest subplot\".<ref name=time>{{cite web |url=http://entertainment.time.com/2011/11/28/walking-dead-recap-pretty-much-dead-already/ |title=Walking Dead Recap: Pretty Much Dead Already |author=Rawlings, Nate |date=28 November 2011 |work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |publisher=Time, Inc. |accessdate=2 January 2012}}</ref> McIntyre felt that the concluding sequence was the most eventful moment of the episode, and stated that it was difficult to watch.<ref name=la/>\n\n[[Ken Tucker]] of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' affirmed that the scene reestablished ''The Walking Dead'' to full form, as well as redeemed the season's \"general gutlessness thus far.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://watching-tv.ew.com/2011/11/28/walking-dead-season-2-episode-7-sophia/|title='The Walking Dead' and 'Pretty Much Dead Already': A cheap thrill-kill, or new life for the season?|first=Ken|last=Tucker|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time, Inc.]]|date=November 28, 2011|accessdate=January 10, 2012}}</ref> [[HitFix]]'s [[Alan Sepinwall]] reflected similar thoughts, and observed that it was effective enough to keep the viewers chattering until the succeeding episode.<ref name=hit>{{cite web|url=http://www.hitfix.com/blogs/whats-alan-watching/posts/the-walking-dead-pretty-much-dead-already-opening-the-barn-door|title=Review: 'The Walking Dead' - 'Pretty Much Dead Already': Opening the barn door|first=Alan|last=Sepinwall|publisher=[[HitFix]]|date=November 27, 2011|accessdate=January 10, 2012}}</ref> Handlen summated: \"The Sophia reveal is a punch in the gut, because narrative fiction teaches us the longer someone stays missing, the better the chance they'll turn up alive; otherwise, where would the drama be? By using the little girl in this way, the show transforms what should've been anti-climax into a reinvention of an entire storyline. It's not enough to make the bad parts of the earlier episodes great, but it does show that the writers had more on their mind than stalling.\"<ref name=av/> Mark Maurer of ''[[The Star-Ledger]]'' felt that albeit predictable, the segment was \"well executed\".<ref name=str>{{cite web|url=http://www.nj.com/entertainment/tv/index.ssf/2011/11/the_walking_dead_midseason_fin.html|title='The Walking Dead' midseason finale recap, 'Pretty Much Dead Already': The new commandments|first=Mark|last=Maurer|work=[[The Star-Ledger]]|publisher=[[Advance Publications]]|date=November 28, 2011|accessdate=January 10, 2012}}</ref> Josh Wigler of [[MTV]] said that the storyline ended in \"a much darker way than anyone could have imagined.\"<ref name=mtv>{{cite web|url=http://splashpage.mtv.com/2011/11/28/walking-dead-season-two-what-do-you-think-so-far/|title='Walking Dead' Season Two: What Do You Think So Far?|first=Josh|last=Wigler|publisher=MTV ([[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]])|date=November 28, 2011|accessdate=January 10, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Speculative fiction/Horror|Television}}\n*[http://www.amctv.com/shows/the-walking-dead/episodes/season-2/pretty-much-dead-already \"Pretty Much Dead Already\"] at [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]]\n*{{IMDb episode|1804271}}\n*{{tv.com episode|the-walking-dead/pretty-much-dead-already-1402831}}\n\n{{The Walking Dead episodes}}\n\n[[Category:2011 American television episodes]]\n[[Category:The Walking Dead (season 2) episodes]]\n", "text_old": "{{Good article}}\n{{Infobox television episode\n|title=Pretty Much Dead Already\n|series=[[The Walking Dead (TV series)|The Walking Dead]]\n|image= PrettyMuchDeadAlreadyWD.jpg\n|caption=[[Rick Grimes|Rick]] tries to convince [[Hershel Greene|Hershel]] to let his group of survivors stay at his ranch.\n|season=2\n|episode=7\n|airdate={{Start date|2011|11|27}}\n|writer=[[Scott M. Gimple]]\n|director=[[Michelle MacLaren]]\n|guests=*[[IronE Singleton]] as [[T-Dog (The Walking Dead)|Theodore \"T-Dog\" Douglas]]\n*[[Madison Lintz]] as [[Sophia Peletier]]\n*[[Lauren Cohan]] as [[Maggie Greene]]\n*[[Emily Kinney]] as [[Beth Greene]]\n*[[Scott Wilson (actor)|Scott Wilson]] as [[Hershel Greene]]\n*[[Jane McNeill]] as Patricia\n*[[James Allen McCune]] as Jimmy\n| season_article = The Walking Dead (season 2)\n| episode_list = List of The Walking Dead episodes\n|prev=[[Secrets (The Walking Dead)|Secrets]]\n|next=[[Nebraska (The Walking Dead)|Nebraska]]\n}}\n\n\"'''Pretty Much Dead Already'''\" is the seventh episode and mid-season finale of the [[The Walking Dead (season 2)|second season]] of the [[Apocalyptic and post-apocalyptic fiction|post-apocalyptic]] [[Horror fiction|horror]] [[television series]] ''[[The Walking Dead (TV series)|The Walking Dead]]''. It originally aired on [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]] in the United States on November 27, 2011. In the episode, Glenn ([[Steven Yeun]]) reveals to the group that there are walkers in the Greenes' barn, dividing the group on what to do. Hershel Greene ([[Scott Wilson (actor)|Scott Wilson]]) sets a deadline for the group to leave, unless [[Rick Grimes]] ([[Andrew Lincoln]]) does a difficult task. Meanwhile, [[Shane Walsh (The Walking Dead)|Shane Walsh]] ([[Jon Bernthal]]) slowly loses his sanity after many secrets around him are revealed and [[Carol Peletier]] begins to question whether her daughter, [[Sophia Peletier|Sophia]] will be found.\n\nThe episode was written by [[Scott M. Gimple]] and directed by [[Michelle MacLaren]]. The death of Sophia Peletier is a prominent theme in \"Pretty Much Dead Already\"; she was killed by Grimes following her conversion into a walker. [[Robert Kirkman]] felt that killing Sophia off would add more dimension to the show, and create more flexibility in regards to the progression of the storylines, as well as leading to very different storylines from the [[The Walking Dead (comic book)|comic series]], with Carol outliving her daughter, as opposed to the other way around. \"Pretty Much Dead Already\" generated critical acclaim, who praised the episode's conclusion and the development of the characters. Upon airing in the United States, the episode attained 6.62 million viewers and a 3.5 rating in the 18-49 demographic, according to [[Nielsen ratings]]. It became the highest-rated cable telecast of the day, as well as the fourth most-viewed cable program of the week.\n\n==Plot==\nGlenn ([[Steven Yeun]]), at the urging of Dale ([[Jeffrey DeMunn]]), finally tells the group that the Greene family's barn is full of [[zombie|walkers]]. The group inspects the barn, and Shane ([[Jon Bernthal]]) believes they should clear the barn, but [[Rick Grimes|Rick]] ([[Andrew Lincoln]]) believes they need to get Hershel ([[Scott Wilson (actor)|Scott Wilson]])'s blessing since they are still guests on his property. Shane criticizes Rick for continuing the seemingly pointless search for Carol ([[Melissa McBride]])'s daughter Sophia, infuriating Daryl ([[Norman Reedus]]).\n\nLater, Maggie Greene ([[Lauren Cohan]]) confronts Glenn about revealing the barn's secret to the group, but Glenn says his personal well-being is more important than her affections. Carol tries to stop Daryl from searching for Sophia alone, but he later comes back to show her another [[Rosa laevigata|Cherokee rose]] blooming, helping to restore Carol's faith they will find Sophia. Elsewhere, Rick confronts Shane about his defiant attitude. The two argue until Rick exclaims that Lori ([[Sarah Wayne Callies]]) is pregnant. As Rick leaves, Shane congratulates him, but is shocked and scared by this revelation.\n\nRick approaches Hershel about the walkers in the barn, but Hershel refuses to allow them to harm the walkers. He, Maggie, and [[Jimmy (The Walking Dead)|Jimmy]] (James Allen McCune) bring Rick to a forest swamp where two walkers are stuck. Hershel insists that if Rick's group is to stay on his farm, they must treat the walkers as people, and shows Rick how to snare and lead the walkers back.\n\nMeanwhile, Shane confronts Lori about her pregnancy, believing himself to be the father. Lori denies this, and Shane storms off, but Carl ([[Chandler Riggs]]) stops him, insisting that they stay and search for Sophia. Dale ([[Jeffrey DeMunn]]), witnessing this, warns Andrea ([[Laurie Holden]]) about Shane's erratic behavior, and then distracts the others long enough to take the weapons from the camp and to hide them in the swamp. Shane discovers the missing weapons and tracks down Dale, demanding he return them. Dale gives in to Shane, but warns him about losing his humanity. Shane replies that they are \"pretty much dead already\".\n\nShane arms the rest of the group and they converge on the barn just as Hershel, Rick, and the others return with the snared walkers. Shane screams that walkers are not people and shoots one of the captive walkers before breaking the locks off the barn doors. Walkers start to file out, and Shane, Andrea, T-Dog ([[IronE Singleton]]), Daryl, and Glenn execute the zombies while the others watch. At the last moment, Sophia ([[Madison Lintz]]) emerges from the barn, dead and zombified. The group is paralyzed with shock and sadness, unable to act as Sophia walks towards them. Only Rick is able to step forward and shoot her.\n\n==Production==\n[[File: Madison Lintz 2014.jpg | thumb | left | 195px | This episode marks the departure of [[Sophia Peletier]], portrayed by [[Madison Lintz]].]]\n{{Quote box |quoted=true |bgcolor=#FFFFF0 |salign=center |width=30% |align=right | quote = Oh yeah, that was her in makeup. That\u2019s the consolation prize to finding out that you're dying on the show. It\u2019s never fun for an actor to learn that they\u2019re being written out of the show and it\u2019s a hard thing to do. It\u2019s something that we never take lightly. But, you know, you\u2019ve got to kill characters! On this show, you at least get the benefit of getting up and coming back as a zombie. That hopefully makes it a little less uncool.|source = '''[[Robert Kirkman]]'''<ref name=ent2/>}}\n\"Pretty Much Dead Already\" was written by [[Scott M. Gimple]] and directed by [[Michelle MacLaren]].<ref name=amc23/> It features recurring appearances from [[Lauren Cohan]], [[Scott Wilson (actor)|Scott Wilson]], [[IronE Singleton]], [[Madison Lintz]], [[Emily Kinney]], [[Jane McNeill]], James Allen McCune, and Amber Chaney.<ref name=amc23>{{cite web|url=http://www.amctv.com/shows/the-walking-dead/episodes/season-2/pretty-much-dead-already|title=Episode 7: Pretty Much Dead Already|publisher=AMC|accessdate=February 26, 2012}}</ref> Following the initial broadcast of the previous installment, \"[[Secrets (The Walking Dead)|Secrets]]\", writer [[Robert Kirkman]] teased the following episode \"Pretty Much Dead Already\". He stated: \"There's a lot of big stuff out there that we will be wrapping up to a certain extent. In the writers' room we were fully aware that we were coming up on this hiatus, so we definitely wrote to it. I think people are going to be a little shocked.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2011/11/21/the-walking-dead-writer-robert-kirkman-secrets/|title='The Walking Dead': Writer Robert Kirkman talks about tonight's episode and teases next week's 'shocking' finale|first=Clark|last=Collis|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time, Inc.]]|date=November 21, 2011|accessdate=January 9, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe death of Sophia Peletier is a major incident in \"Pretty Much Dead Already\", largely affecting the themes of the episode. After the group has shot the walkers housed in Hershel Greene's barn, Sophia appears from the barn as a walker, much to the groups' dismay. A disturbed and distraught Rick Grimes pulls out his weapon and makes the decision to shoot her. Despite being initially surprised about her character's being killed off, Madison Lintz concluded that she understood its aftermath for the show.<ref name=amc>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.amctv.com/the-walking-dead/2012/01/madison-lintz-interview.php|title=Q&A - Madison Lintz (Sophia)|last=Rosenburg|first=Eli|publisher=[[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]]|date=January 2, 2012|accessdate=January 9, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120107201903/http://blogs.amctv.com/the-walking-dead/2012/01/madison-lintz-interview.php|archivedate=January 7, 2012}}</ref> Lintz affirmed that portraying a walker was a welcoming experience for her, and stated that she was \"going to look back on and say that was amazing.\"<ref name=amc/> Robert Kirkman felt that killing Sophia would add more dimension to the show, as well as add more flexibility to its storyline progression. \"When a good idea comes up, you have to go with it,\" he articulated.<ref name=hr/> \"Sophia is a character who is still alive in the comic book series and who has contributed quite a bit to the overall narrative and informed a lot of story lines for a lot of different characters. Having Carol [...] survive her daughter as opposed to the other way around as it is in the comics is going to lead to interesting but different stories.\"<ref name=hr>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/walking-dead-midseason-finale-robert-kirkman-265484|title='The Walking Dead' Dissection: Robert Kirkman Talks Death and What's Ahead|first=Leslie|last=Goldberg|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|date=November 27, 2011|accessdate=January 9, 2012}}</ref> Although Kirkman was not on set during production of the sequence, Gimple retrieved shell casings from the [[blank (cartridge)|blanks]] that were fired on set.<ref name=ent2/> Referred to as \"Barnageddon\" by the writers, Kirkman asserted that he emphasized unpredictability while creating the scene.<ref name=ent2>{{cite web|url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2011/11/28/walking-dead-finale-kirkman-2/|title='Walking Dead' writer Robert Kirkman talks midseason finale shocker|first=Clark|last=Collis|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time, Inc.]]|date=November 28, 2011|accessdate=January 9, 2012}}</ref>\n<blockquote>\nIt's good to know people didn't see it coming. That's a big concern when you have this kind of story line and you are leading to that kind of reveal. You don't want people to be expecting it, especially in the ''Walking Dead''. I pride myself in the fact that, when you pick up an issue of the comic, you don't know what's going to happen at any time. So any time we can work that into the show and maintain that in a television environment, it's very exciting for me. I\u2019m glad people are being caught off guard.<ref name=ent2/>\n</blockquote>\nOther themes prevalent in the episode include Lori's pregnancy. After getting into a heated argument, Rick reveals to Shane about her pregnancy. Although he didn't question who the biological father was, Robert Kirkman felt that Rick was \"smart enough to know that the kid's either his or Shane's and there may not be any way of ever finding out that definitively.\"<ref name=ent2/> He continued: \"Bringing that up to his wife, who he loves, is only going to be painful for her. I think that\u2019s him being a good husband and him showing his tremendous leadership ability in that he can put his self aside for the betterment of someone else.\"<ref name=ent2/>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Ratings===\n\"Pretty Much Dead Already\" was initially broadcast in November 27, 2011 in the United States on AMC. Upon airing, it garnered 6.62 million viewers and a 3.5 rating in the 18-49 demographic, according to [[Nielsen ratings]]. The episode became the highest-rated cable program of the day, obtaining significantly higher ratings than ''[[Kourtney and Kim Take New York]]'' on [[E!]] and ''[[Real Housewives of Atlanta]]'' on [[Bravo (US TV channel)|Bravo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2011/11/29/sunday-cable-ratings-the-walking-dead-goes-out-on-top-kardashians-housewives-soul-train-awards-hell-on-wheels-boardwalk-empire-homeland-dexter-more/112136/|title=Sunday Cable Ratings: 'The Walking Dead' Goes Out on Top + Kardashians, 'Housewives' 'Soul Train Awards,' 'Hell On Wheels,' 'Boardwalk Empire,' 'Homeland,' 'Dexter' & More|publisher=[[TV by the Numbers]]|last=Seidman|first=Robert|date=November 29, 2011|accessdate=November 30, 2011}}</ref> \"Pretty Much Dead Already\" received the show's highest ratings since \"[[Bloodletting (The Walking Dead)|Bloodletting]]\", which obtained 6.7 million viewers and a 3.6 rating in the 18-49 demographic.<ref name=tvratings>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2011/10/25/sunday-cable-ratings-the-walking-dead-slips-still-tops-nj-housewives-boardwalk-empire-homeland-dexter-much-more/108350/|title=Sunday Cable Ratings: 'The Walking Dead' Slips, Still Tops; + NJ Housewives, 'Boardwalk Empire,' 'Homeland,' 'Dexter' & Much More|publisher=[[TV by the Numbers]]|last=Gorman|first=Bill|date=October 25, 2011|accessdate=January 9, 2012}}</ref> In addition, the episode became the fourth highest-rated cable telecast of the week, and the highest-rated non sport cable telecast of the week dated November 27.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2011/11/29/cable-top-25-nfl-football-the-walking-dead-top-weekly-cable-viewing-for-the-week-ending-nov-27-2011/112169/|title=Cable Top 25: NFL Football, 'The Walking Dead' Top Weekly Cable Viewing for the Week Ending Nov 27, 2011|publisher=[[TV by the Numbers]]|last=Seidman|first=Robert|date=November 27, 2011|accessdate=January 9, 2012}}</ref> Total viewership and ratings for the episode significantly increased from the preceding installment, \"[[Secrets (The Walking Dead)|Secrets]]\", which garnered 6.08 million viewers and a 3.1 rating amongst adults in the 18-49 demographic.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2011/11/22/sunday-cable-ratings-the-walking-dead-stays-on-top-nascar-championship-housewives-atl-hell-on-wheels-boardwalk-empire-homeland-dexter-more/111468/|title=Sunday Cable Ratings: 'The Walking Dead' Stays On Top + NASCAR Championship, 'Housewives ATL,' 'Hell On Wheels,' 'Boardwalk Empire,' 'Homeland,' 'Dexter' & More|publisher=[[TV by the Numbers]]|last=Gorman|first=Bill|date=November 22, 2010|accessdate=January 9, 2012}}</ref> In the United Kingdom, \"Pretty Much Dead Already\" received 666,000 viewers, subsequently becoming the most-watched cable program on [[Fox (UK and Ireland)|FX]] of the week dated December 4.<ref>{{cite press|url=http://www.barb.co.uk/whats-new/weekly-top-10? |title=Weekly Top 10 Programmes |publisher=[[Broadcasters' Audience Research Board]] |accessdate=January 9, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140718204656/http://www.barb.co.uk/whats-new/weekly-top-10 |archivedate=July 18, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\n{{Quote box |quoted=true |bgcolor=#FFFFF0 |salign=center |width=30% |align=right | quote = \"Pretty Much Dead Already\" tied up the immediate loose ends, and like Season 1's \"[[TS-19]]\", contained a noisy last five minutes. Your opinion on the episode depends on how engaged you were in the season so far. As soon as the barn doors opened, the events were well executed, albeit foreseeable|source = '''Mark Maurer<br>''The Star Ledger'''''<ref name=str/>}}\n\"Pretty Much Dead Already\" was critically acclaimed by television critics and is generally considered to be one of the best episodes of the series. Eric Goldman of [[IGN]] evaluated the episode as \"completely depressing\", and added that the dark nature made the series excel. Goldman ultimately gave the episode an eight out of ten, signifying a \"great\" rating.<ref name=ign>{{cite web |url=http://tv.ign.com/articles/121/1213275p1.html |title=The Walking Dead: \"Pretty Much Dead Already\" Review |last=Goldman|first=Eric|date=November 27, 2011 |publisher=IGN|accessdate=January 2, 2012}}</ref> Aaron Rutkoff of ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' felt that the episode was the series' best installment.<ref name=\"Rutkoff\">{{cite news|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2011/11/27/the-walking-dead-season-2-episode-7-pretty-much-dead-already-tv-recap/?mod=google_news_blog|title='The Walking Dead,' Season 2, Episode 7, 'Pretty Much Dead Already' Midseason Finale|last=Rutkoff|first=Aaron|date=November 27, 2011|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|accessdate=November 28, 2011}}</ref> Writing for ''[[The Grand Rapids Press]]'', John Serba opined that \"Pretty Much Dead Already\" was a delightful ending to the first portion of the season.<ref name=serba>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlive.com/movies/index.ssf/2011/11/walking_dead_postmortem_pretty.html|title='Walking Dead' postmortem, 'Pretty Much Dead Already': Conclusive arguments about the right to zombie life|first=John|last=Serba|work=[[The Grand Rapids Press]]|publisher=Dan Gaydou|date=November 28, 2011|accessdate=January 10, 2012}}</ref> Zack Handlen of ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' stated that prior to its ending, the episode was \"the usual mix of pretty good and deeply irritating.\"<ref name=av/> Handlen lauded the character development in the installment; \"The episode puts a lot of effort into heightening the tensions between Hershel and Rick's people, and while it\u2019s not exactly subtle, it makes enough sense to be effective. This is conflict that should've been building for a few episodes now, instead of arriving fully formed right before it explodes, but I'm willing to take what I can get.\"<ref name=av>{{cite web|url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/pretty-much-dead-already,65692/|title=Pretty Much Dead Already|last=Handlen|first=Zack|date=November 28, 2011|accessdate=January 10, 2012|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|publisher=[[The Onion]]}}</ref> Concluding his review, he issued the episode an A\u2013 grade.<ref name=av/> [[Digital Spy]]'s Morgan Jeffrey avouched that \"Pretty Much Dead Already\" was \"excellent\", and added that the tension \"slowly ratchets up to an almost unbearable level.\"<ref name=digi>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/s135/the-walking-dead/recaps/a352768/the-walking-dead-pretty-much-dead-already-recap.html|title='The Walking Dead': 'Pretty Much Dead Already' recap|first=Morgan|last=Jeffrey|publisher=[[Digital Spy]]|date=November 28, 2011|accessdate=January 10, 2012}}</ref> Some critics were divided with the episode. ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' journalist Nate Rawlings felt that while the writers put a lot of substance into the characters, many of them are still underdeveloped.<ref name=time/> Gina McIntyre of ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' felt that some parts of the episode lacked cohesion and direction.<ref name=la>{{cite web|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/showtracker/2011/11/walking-dead-recap-pretty-much-dead-already.html|title='The Walking Dead' recap: They shoot zombies, don't they?|first=Gina|last=McIntyre|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]|date=November 28, 2011|accessdate=January 10, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe episode's concluding scene involving Sophia's death was cited as the episode highlight. Janet Turley of ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' asserted that the sequence was \"fiction not afraid to provoke\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/janet-turley/the-walking-dead-midseries-recap_b_1116624.html|title=The Walking Dead Midseries Finale: Pretty Much Dead Already|work=[[Huffington Post]]|publisher=[[Arianna Huffington]]|first=Janet|last=Turley|date=November 28, 2011|accessdate=January 9, 2012}}</ref> while Goldman described it as an \"absolutely horrific scenario\".<ref name=ign/> [[CNN]]'s Henry Hanks opined that the sequence \"left [them] with a final scene that we'll be talking about until then.\"<ref name=\"Hanks\">{{cite news|url=http://marquee.blogs.cnn.com/2011/11/28/things-come-to-a-head-on-the-walking-dead/|title=Things come to a head on 'The Walking Dead'|last=Hanks|first=Henry|date=November 28, 2011|publisher=CNN|accessdate=November 28, 2011}}</ref> ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]''{{'s}} Starlee Kine asserted that it contained cinematic qualities, and felt that the scene was \"satisfying, sad, and fun\".<ref name=\"Kine\">{{cite news|url=http://nymag.com/daily/entertainment/2011/11/walking-dead-the-walking-dead-recap-finders-fee.html|title=The Walking Dead Recap: Finder\u2019s Fee|last=Kine|first=Starlee|date=November 28, 2011|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|publisher=New York Media|accessdate=January 9, 2012}}</ref> She wrote: \"It was everything you've ever wanted this show to be. Zombies plus no dialogue, such a winning combination! And how great was it that Sophia was dead instead of impossibly alive somewhere, holed up with Merle or Morgan or those warmhearted gang members in Atlanta. And because she was granted more screen time than she ever was when she was alive, we were finally able to care about the loss of her short, young life.\"<ref name=\"Kine\"/> Jen Chaney of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' echoed synonymous sentiments; \"Really, the final moments of the last episode before the AMC series' December/January hiatus played like a fireworks finale on the Fourth of July, assuming your Fourth of July celebrations typically involve zombies and a pile of corpses.\"<ref name=wp>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/celebritology/post/walking-dead-in-pretty-much-dead-already-they-shoot-zombies-dont-they/2011/11/27/gIQA5Lai3N_blog.html|title=\u2018Walking Dead\u2019: In \u2018Pretty Much Dead Already,\u2019 they shoot zombies, don\u2019t they?|first=Jen|last=Chenay|work=[[The Washington Post]]|publisher=[[The Washington Post Company]]|date=November 28, 2011|accessdate= January 10, 2012}}</ref> Rawlings concluded that it was the perfect resolution for what he called \"television's slowest subplot\".<ref name=time>{{cite web |url=http://entertainment.time.com/2011/11/28/walking-dead-recap-pretty-much-dead-already/ |title=Walking Dead Recap: Pretty Much Dead Already |author=Rawlings, Nate |date=28 November 2011 |work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |publisher=Time, Inc. |accessdate=2 January 2012}}</ref> McIntyre felt that the concluding sequence was the most eventful moment of the episode, and stated that it was difficult to watch.<ref name=la/>\n\n[[Ken Tucker]] of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' affirmed that the scene reestablished ''The Walking Dead'' to full form, as well as redeemed the season's \"general gutlessness thus far.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://watching-tv.ew.com/2011/11/28/walking-dead-season-2-episode-7-sophia/|title='The Walking Dead' and 'Pretty Much Dead Already': A cheap thrill-kill, or new life for the season?|first=Ken|last=Tucker|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time, Inc.]]|date=November 28, 2011|accessdate=January 10, 2012}}</ref> [[HitFix]]'s [[Alan Sepinwall]] reflected similar thoughts, and observed that it was effective enough to keep the viewers chattering until the succeeding episode.<ref name=hit>{{cite web|url=http://www.hitfix.com/blogs/whats-alan-watching/posts/the-walking-dead-pretty-much-dead-already-opening-the-barn-door|title=Review: 'The Walking Dead' - 'Pretty Much Dead Already': Opening the barn door|first=Alan|last=Sepinwall|publisher=[[HitFix]]|date=November 27, 2011|accessdate=January 10, 2012}}</ref> Handlen summated: \"The Sophia reveal is a punch in the gut, because narrative fiction teaches us the longer someone stays missing, the better the chance they'll turn up alive; otherwise, where would the drama be? By using the little girl in this way, the show transforms what should've been anti-climax into a reinvention of an entire storyline. It's not enough to make the bad parts of the earlier episodes great, but it does show that the writers had more on their mind than stalling.\"<ref name=av/> Mark Maurer of ''[[The Star-Ledger]]'' felt that albeit predictable, the segment was \"well executed\".<ref name=str>{{cite web|url=http://www.nj.com/entertainment/tv/index.ssf/2011/11/the_walking_dead_midseason_fin.html|title='The Walking Dead' midseason finale recap, 'Pretty Much Dead Already': The new commandments|first=Mark|last=Maurer|work=[[The Star-Ledger]]|publisher=[[Advance Publications]]|date=November 28, 2011|accessdate=January 10, 2012}}</ref> Josh Wigler of [[MTV]] said that the storyline ended in \"a much darker way than anyone could have imagined.\"<ref name=mtv>{{cite web|url=http://splashpage.mtv.com/2011/11/28/walking-dead-season-two-what-do-you-think-so-far/|title='Walking Dead' Season Two: What Do You Think So Far?|first=Josh|last=Wigler|publisher=MTV ([[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]])|date=November 28, 2011|accessdate=January 10, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Speculative fiction/Horror|Television}}\n*[http://www.amctv.com/shows/the-walking-dead/episodes/season-2/pretty-much-dead-already \"Pretty Much Dead Already\"] at [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]]\n*{{IMDb episode|1804271}}\n*{{tv.com episode|the-walking-dead/pretty-much-dead-already-1402831}}\n\n{{The Walking Dead episodes}}\n\n[[Category:2011 American television episodes]]\n[[Category:The Walking Dead (season 2) episodes]]\n", "name_user": "Jamesmc56", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pretty_Much_Dead_Already"}
{"title_page": "Egglescliffe School", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox school\n | name                    = Egglescliffe School & Sixth Form College\n | image                   = Y1oP8WtN.jpg\n | image_size              = \n | coordinates             = {{coord|54.516450|-1.360525|type:edu_region:GB_dim:100|format=dec|display=inline,title}}\n | motto                   = Forward Together\n | established             = 1962\n | closed                  = \n | type                    = [[Community school (England and Wales)|Community school]]\n | religious_affiliation   = \n | president               = \n | head_label              = Headteacher\n | head                    = Simon White\n | r_head_label            = \n | r_head                  = \n | chair_label             = \n | chair                   = \n | founder                 = \n | address                 = Urlay Nook Road<br />[[Eaglescliffe]]\n | city                    = [[Stockton-on-Tees]]\n | county                  = [[County Durham]]\n | country                 = England\n | postcode                = TS16 0LA\n | local_authority         = [[Stockton-on-Tees Borough Council|Stockton-on-Tees]]\n | ofsted                  = yes\n | dfeno                   = 808/4008\n | urn                     = 111727\n | staff                   = \n | enrolment               = 1,459 (with 300 in the sixth form)\n | lower_age               = 11\n | upper_age               = 18\n | gender                  = Mixed\n | houses                  = Aldrin / Armstrong / Gagarin (Lower houses) Tereshkova / Lovell (Upper houses )\n | colours                 = Navy, black, and white<br />{{color box|Navy}} {{color box|Black}} {{color box|White}}\n | publication             = \n | free_2                  = \n | free_label_3            = \n | free_3                  = \n | website                 = http://egglescliffe.org.uk/\n}}\n\n'''Egglescliffe School & Sixth Form College''' is a large [[Mixed-sex education|mixed]] [[comprehensive school]] and [[sixth form]] in [[Eaglescliffe]], [[Stockton-on-Tees]], [[County Durham]] for students aged 11 to 18.\n\n== History ==\nBeginning as a small rural [[secondary school]] of 200 pupils in 1962, Egglescliffe became a comprehensive in the 1970s, gradually growing to its current size of over 1400 pupils, including [[sixth form]]ers. There have been five headteachers since it opened: Mr. Frank Davison, Mr. Alan Basset, Mr. David Oliver, Mrs. Angela Darnell and Mr. Simon White. In 2010, Mrs Darnell was awarded an [[Order of the British Empire|OBE]] for \"services to education\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gazettelive.co.uk/news/local-news/egglescliffe-teacher-angela-darnell-awarded-3703271|title=Egglescliffe teacher Angela Darnell awarded OBE|last=Evening|first=Gazette|date=12 June 2010|website=[[Evening Gazette (Teesside)|GazetteLive]]}}</ref>  In 2012 the school celebrated its 50th anniversary.\n\n== Academic achievements ==\nIn 1999, Egglescliffe was awarded [[Specialist schools programme|''Specialist Status'']] and designated an [[Arts College]] specialising in music and drama, since then refurbishment of the music block has transformed the interior structure of the department. Its Music Department has a longstanding reputation for performance work. The school has also been designated a National Teaching school. These are outstanding schools which have been nationally recognised for their capacity to support and help other schools to improve outcomes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tscouncil.org.uk/what-is-a-teaching-school/|title=What is a Teaching School|website=Teaching Schools Council|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n=== Anthony Gears and the Drama Department  ===\nFrom 1999 until his death on 25 June 2010, it was under the direction of Anthony Gears, joined by a team of six, teaching drama and theatre. He was succeeded as Director of Performing Arts by Harmony Gibson, his daughter.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.gazettelive.co.uk/news/local-news/teacher-succeeds-dad-egglescliffe-school-3697254 | title=Teacher succeeds dad at Egglescliffe School | website=[[Evening Gazette (Teesside)|GazetteLive]] | date=7 October 2010 | last=Passant | first=Andy}}</ref>\n\nA specialist theatre was built to host the many Drama and Theatre productions throughout the school year. It is also home to Egglescliffe Youth Theatre, launched in its present form in September 1986, now one of the longest-running Theatre groups in the country. It holds weekly sessions and yearly summer productions.\n\n=== The Music Department  ===\nHead of the  Music Department for 32 years was Keith Hewson, who retired in 2008. Over those years his Orchestras, Brass Bands, Choirs, Jazz Ensembles and Chamber Groups appeared at the Music for Youth National Festival over 80 times winning many outstanding performance awards and appearing at the Royal Albert Hall School proms on 19 occasions. For over ten years Hewson was a member of the government's Music and Dance Scheme Panel and the Specialist Schools Music Expert Panel. In 2002 he was voted Classic FM Music Teacher of the Year.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.panpodium.com/steelbands-north-newsletter-spring-2013-edition/ | title=Steelbands North Newsletter | website=Pan Podium | date=March 2013}}</ref>\nIn April 2008, following the award of [[Specialist schools programme#High Performing Specialist Status|High Performing Specialist Status]] the school was designated a second specialism as a [[Science College]].  In 2012, the current Head of Music, Matthew Haworth, was awarded the Secondary Music Teacher of the Year by [[Classic FM (UK)|Classic FM]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.classicfm.com/concerts-events/music-teacher-year/news/music-teacher-year-winners-announced/ | title=More Music Teacher of the Year winners announced | website=[[Classic FM (UK)|Classic FM]] | date=14 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.classicfm.com/concerts-events/schools-prom/performers/egglescliffe-school-brass-band/ | title=Egglescliffe School Brass Band | website=[[Classic FM (UK)|Classic FM]]}}</ref> In recent years the various ensembles of the school have played in a number of significant venues such as [[Symphony Hall, Birmingham|Symphony Hall Birmingham]], [[Ely Cathedral]], [[Durham Cathedral]], [[Birmingham Town Hall|Town Hall Birmingham]], [[Sage Gateshead|The Sage Gateshead]], [[St Mark's Basilica|St Marks Venice]], [[Royal Albert Hall|The Royal Albert Hall]] and [[Winter Gardens, Blackpool|Blackpool Winter Gardens]].  \n\n===The Science Department (Physics)===\nOver the last 25 years many Physics students from Egglescliffe have gone on to university to excel academically in their degree courses in physics, astronomy or engineering, following this with interesting and varied careers. Some of these ex-students are profiled on the Physics Homepage - see 'External Links' below.\n\n== Notable Visitors to Egglescliffe School ==\n\n* [[Tony Blair]] (Former British Prime Minister)\n* [[Caroline Flint]] (Former Shadow Energy Secretary)\n* [[Doug Scott]] (Mountaineer) \n* [[James Wharton]] (Former MP for Stockton South)\n* [[Paul McCreesh]] (artistic director of the Gabrieli Consort & Players) \n* \n\n== ''The South Bank Show'' ==\nThe school featured in an episode of ''[[The South Bank Show]]'' titled \"[[Howard Goodall]] \u2014 A Musical Nation\" that aired on Sunday 19 December 2004 on [[ITV (TV channel)|ITV]], in which he explored Britain's musical provision for young people.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.gazettelive.co.uk/news/local-news/pupils-star-top-tv-show-3825218 | title=Pupils to star in top TV show | website=[[Evening Gazette (Teesside)|GazetteLive]] | date=13 July 2004 | last=Evening | first=Gazette}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.howardgoodall.co.uk/works/tv-presenting/south-bank-show-a-musical-nation/research-for-a-musical-nation | title=Research for A Musical Nation | website=[[Howard Goodall]]}}</ref>\n\n== 50th anniversary concert ==\nThe concert, performed at the [[Sage Gateshead|Sage, Gateshead]] on 15 July 2012, was a huge success.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.egglescliffe-arts.org.uk/Anniversary.html | title=50th Anniversary Concert | website=Egglescliffe Creative Arts | date=15 July 2012 | access-date=2 October 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131023055836/http://www.egglescliffe-arts.org.uk/Anniversary.html | archive-date=23 October 2013 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== Notable former pupils ==\nAndrew Levan \u2014 Professor of Physics at [[University of Warwick|Warwick University]], won ''The [[Philip Leverhulme Prize]]'' in 2011 for ''Astronomy and Astrophysics'', for his research into Gamma-ray bursts, supernovae and high redshift galaxies.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.leverhulme.ac.uk/templates/asset-relay.cfm?frmAssetFileID=925 |title=Philip Leverhulme Prize Winners 2011 |website=The [[Leverhulme Trust]] }}{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The prizes, each worth \u00a370,000, are awarded to outstanding scholars who have made a substantial contribution to their particular field of study, recognised at an international level and where the expectation is that their greatest achievement is yet to come. In October 2017 Professor Levan announced (at an international press conference in Munich) discovery of a neutron star 'kilonova' having detected synchronous gravitational waves and optical signals. This has been heralded as all but conclusive evidence for gravitational radiation. Andrew was leader of the Hubble Space Telescope team for this project which involved collaboration between observers from 18 countries.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://egglescliffe.org.uk School homepage]\n\n{{Schools in County Durham}}\n\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1962]]\n[[Category:1962 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Secondary schools in the Borough of Stockton-on-Tees]]\n[[Category:Community schools in the Borough of Stockton-on-Tees]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox school\n | name                    = Egglescliffe School & Sixth Form College\n | image                   = Y1oP8WtN.jpg\n | image_size              = \n | coordinates             = {{coord|54.516450|-1.360525|type:edu_region:GB_dim:100|format=dec|display=inline,title}}\n | motto                   = Forward Together\n | established             = 1962\n | closed                  = \n | type                    = [[Community school (England and Wales)|Community school]]\n | religious_affiliation   = \n | president               = \n | head_label              = Headteacher\n | head                    = Simon White\n | r_head_label            = \n | r_head                  = \n | chair_label             = \n | chair                   = \n | founder                 = \n | address                 = Urlay Nook Road<br />[[Eaglescliffe]]\n | city                    = [[Stockton-on-Tees]]\n | county                  = [[County Durham]]\n | country                 = England\n | postcode                = TS16 0LA\n | local_authority         = [[Stockton-on-Tees Borough Council|Stockton-on-Tees]]\n | ofsted                  = yes\n | dfeno                   = 808/4008\n | urn                     = 111727\n | staff                   = \n | enrolment               = 1,459 (with 300 in the sixth form)\n | lower_age               = 11\n | upper_age               = 18\n | gender                  = Mixed\n | houses                  = Aldrin / Armstrong / Gagarin (Lower houses) Tereshkova / Lovell (Upper houses )\n | colours                 = Navy, black, and white<br />{{color box|Navy}} {{color box|Black}} {{color box|White}}\n | publication             = \n | free_2                  = \n | free_label_3            = \n | free_3                  = \n | website                 = http://egglescliffe.org.uk/\n}}\n\n'''Egglescliffe School & Sixth Form College''' is a large [[Mixed-sex education|mixed]] [[comprehensive school]] and [[sixth form]] in [[Eaglescliffe]], [[Stockton-on-Tees]], [[County Durham]] for students aged 11 to 18.\n\n== History ==\nBeginning as a small rural [[secondary school]] of 200 pupils in 1962, Egglescliffe became a comprehensive in the 1970s, gradually growing to its current size of over 1400 pupils, including [[sixth form]]ers. There have been five headteachers since it opened: Mr. Frank Davison, Mr. Alan Basset, Mr. David Oliver, Mrs. Angela Darnell and Mr. Simon White. In 2010, Mrs Darnell was awarded an [[Order of the British Empire|OBE]] for \"services to education\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gazettelive.co.uk/news/local-news/egglescliffe-teacher-angela-darnell-awarded-3703271|title=Egglescliffe teacher Angela Darnell awarded OBE|last=Evening|first=Gazette|date=12 June 2010|website=[[Evening Gazette (Teesside)|GazetteLive]]}}</ref>  In 2012 the school celebrated its 50th anniversary.\n\n== Academic achievements ==\nIn 1999, Egglescliffe was awarded [[Specialist schools programme|''Specialist Status'']] and designated an [[Arts College]] specialising in music and drama, since then refurbishment of the music block has transformed the interior structure of the department. Its Music Department has a longstanding reputation for performance work. The school has also been designated a National Teaching school. These are outstanding schools which have been nationally recognised for their capacity to support and help other schools to improve outcomes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tscouncil.org.uk/what-is-a-teaching-school/|title=What is a Teaching School|website=Teaching Schools Council|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n=== Anthony Gears and the Drama Department  ===\nFrom 1999 until his death on 25 June 2010, it was under the direction of Anthony Gears, joined by a team of six, teaching drama and theatre. He was succeeded as Director of Performing Arts by Harmony Gibson, his daughter.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.gazettelive.co.uk/news/local-news/teacher-succeeds-dad-egglescliffe-school-3697254 | title=Teacher succeeds dad at Egglescliffe School | website=[[Evening Gazette (Teesside)|GazetteLive]] | date=7 October 2010 | last=Passant | first=Andy}}</ref>\n\nA specialist theatre was built to host the many Drama and Theatre productions throughout the school year. It is also home to Egglescliffe Youth Theatre, launched in its present form in September 1986, now one of the longest-running Theatre groups in the country. It holds weekly sessions and yearly summer productions.\n\n=== The Music Department  ===\nHead of the  Music Department for 32 years was Keith Hewson, who retired in 2008. Over those years his Orchestras, Brass Bands, Choirs, Jazz Ensembles and Chamber Groups appeared at the Music for Youth National Festival over 80 times winning many outstanding performance awards and appearing at the Royal Albert Hall School proms on 19 occasions. For over ten years Hewson was a member of the government's Music and Dance Scheme Panel and the Specialist Schools Music Expert Panel. In 2002 he was voted Classic FM Music Teacher of the Year.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.panpodium.com/steelbands-north-newsletter-spring-2013-edition/ | title=Steelbands North Newsletter | website=Pan Podium | date=March 2013}}</ref>\nIn April 2008, following the award of [[Specialist schools programme#High Performing Specialist Status|High Performing Specialist Status]] the school was designated a second specialism as a [[Science College]].  In 2012, the current Head of Music, Matthew Haworth, was awarded the Secondary Music Teacher of the Year by [[Classic FM (UK)|Classic FM]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.classicfm.com/concerts-events/music-teacher-year/news/music-teacher-year-winners-announced/ | title=More Music Teacher of the Year winners announced | website=[[Classic FM (UK)|Classic FM]] | date=14 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.classicfm.com/concerts-events/schools-prom/performers/egglescliffe-school-brass-band/ | title=Egglescliffe School Brass Band | website=[[Classic FM (UK)|Classic FM]]}}</ref> In recent years the various ensembles of of the school have played in a number of significant venues such as [[Symphony Hall, Birmingham|Symphony Hall Birmingham]], [[Ely Cathedral]], [[Durham Cathedral]], [[Birmingham Town Hall|Town Hall Birmingham]], [[Sage Gateshead|The Sage Gateshead]], [[St Mark's Basilica|St Marks Venice]], [[Royal Albert Hall|The Royal Albert Hall]] and [[Winter Gardens, Blackpool|Blackpool Winter Gardens]].  \n\n===The Science Department (Physics)===\nOver the last 25 years many Physics students from Egglescliffe have gone on to university to excel academically in their degree courses in physics, astronomy or engineering, following this with interesting and varied careers. Some of these ex-students are profiled on the Physics Homepage - see 'External Links' below.\n\n== Notable Visitors to Egglescliffe School ==\n\n* [[Tony Blair]] (Former British Prime Minister)\n* [[Caroline Flint]] (Former Shadow Energy Secretary)\n* [[Doug Scott]] (Mountaineer) \n* [[James Wharton]] (Former MP for Stockton South)\n* [[Paul McCreesh]] (artistic director of the Gabrieli Consort & Players) \n* \n\n== ''The South Bank Show'' ==\nThe school featured in an episode of ''[[The South Bank Show]]'' titled \"[[Howard Goodall]] \u2014 A Musical Nation\" that aired on Sunday 19 December 2004 on [[ITV (TV channel)|ITV]], in which he explored Britain's musical provision for young people.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.gazettelive.co.uk/news/local-news/pupils-star-top-tv-show-3825218 | title=Pupils to star in top TV show | website=[[Evening Gazette (Teesside)|GazetteLive]] | date=13 July 2004 | last=Evening | first=Gazette}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.howardgoodall.co.uk/works/tv-presenting/south-bank-show-a-musical-nation/research-for-a-musical-nation | title=Research for A Musical Nation | website=[[Howard Goodall]]}}</ref>\n\n== 50th anniversary concert ==\nThe concert, performed at the [[Sage Gateshead|Sage, Gateshead]] on 15 July 2012, was a huge success.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.egglescliffe-arts.org.uk/Anniversary.html | title=50th Anniversary Concert | website=Egglescliffe Creative Arts | date=15 July 2012 | access-date=2 October 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131023055836/http://www.egglescliffe-arts.org.uk/Anniversary.html | archive-date=23 October 2013 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== Notable former pupils ==\nAndrew Levan \u2014 Professor of Physics at [[University of Warwick|Warwick University]], won ''The [[Philip Leverhulme Prize]]'' in 2011 for ''Astronomy and Astrophysics'', for his research into Gamma-ray bursts, supernovae and high redshift galaxies.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.leverhulme.ac.uk/templates/asset-relay.cfm?frmAssetFileID=925 |title=Philip Leverhulme Prize Winners 2011 |website=The [[Leverhulme Trust]] }}{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The prizes, each worth \u00a370,000, are awarded to outstanding scholars who have made a substantial contribution to their particular field of study, recognised at an international level and where the expectation is that their greatest achievement is yet to come. In October 2017 Professor Levan announced (at an international press conference in Munich) discovery of a neutron star 'kilonova' having detected synchronous gravitational waves and optical signals. This has been heralded as all but conclusive evidence for gravitational radiation. Andrew was leader of the Hubble Space Telescope team for this project which involved collaboration between observers from 18 countries.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://egglescliffe.org.uk School homepage]\n\n{{Schools in County Durham}}\n\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1962]]\n[[Category:1962 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Secondary schools in the Borough of Stockton-on-Tees]]\n[[Category:Community schools in the Borough of Stockton-on-Tees]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Egglescliffe_School"}
{"title_page": "Because (Beatles song)", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=June 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2012}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Because\n| cover      = Because sheet music.PNG\n| cover_size = 160px\n| caption    = Cover of the song's sheet music\n| artist     = [[the Beatles]]\n| album      = [[Abbey Road]]\n| released   = {{Start date|1969|09|26|df=y}}\n| recorded   = 1\u20135 August 1969\n| studio     = [[Abbey Road Studios|EMI]], London\n| genre      = <!--- Do not add unsourced genres --->\n| length     = {{Duration|m=2|s=45}}\n| writer     = [[Lennon\u2013McCartney]]\n| label      = [[Apple Records|Apple]]\n| producer   = [[George Martin]]\n| misc       = {{Audio sample\n | type = song\n | file = Because Beatles.ogg\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Because'''\" is a song written by [[John Lennon]]{{sfn|Sheff|2000|p=191}} (credited to [[Lennon\u2013McCartney]]) and recorded by the English rock band [[the Beatles]]. It was released on their 1969 album ''[[Abbey Road]]'', immediately preceding the extended [[Medley (music)|medley]] on side two of the record. It features a prominent three-part vocal harmony by Lennon, [[Paul McCartney]], and [[George Harrison]], recorded three times to make nine voices in all.\n\n==Composition==\n[[File:Harp02.jpg|thumb|An [[electric harpsichord]] similar to the one used for \"Because\"]]\n\nThe song begins with a distinctive [[Electric piano#Other electric keyboard instruments|electric harpsichord]] intro played by producer [[George Martin]]. The harpsichord is joined by Lennon's guitar (mimicking the harpsichord line) played through a [[Leslie speaker]]. Then vocals and bass guitar enter.\n\n\"Because\" was one of few Beatles recordings to feature a [[Moog synthesizer|Moog synthesiser]], played by George Harrison. It appears in what [[Alan W. Pollack|Alan Pollack]] refers to as the \"mini-bridge\",{{sfn|Pollack}} and then again at the end of the song.\n\nAccording to Lennon, the song's close musical resemblance to the first movement of [[Ludwig van Beethoven]]'s ''[[Piano Sonata No. 14 (Beethoven)|Moonlight Sonata]]'' was no coincidence: \"[[Yoko Ono|Yoko]] was playing Beethoven's 'Moonlight Sonata' on the piano ... I said, 'Can you play those chords backwards?', and wrote 'Because' around them. The lyrics speak for themselves ... No imagery, no obscure references.\"{{sfn|Sheff|2000|p=191}}{{sfn|Snopes.com|2009|pp=1}}\n\n==Musical structure==\nWith regard to the controversy Lennon initiated by citing Beethoven's \"[[Moonlight Sonata]]\" as an inspiration,{{clarify |date=November 2017 |reason=What controversy? }} musicologist [[Walter Everett (musicologist)|Walter Everett]] notes that \"both arpeggiate triads and seventh chords in [[C-sharp minor|C{{music|sharp}} minor]] in the [[baritone]] range of a keyboard instrument at a slow tempo, move through the [[submediant]] to [[Neapolitan chord|{{music|flat}}II]] and approach [[subtonic|vii]] [[Diminished seventh chord|dim<sup>7</sup>]]/IV via a common tone.\"<ref>Walter Everett. ''The Beatles as Musicians: Revolver Through the Anthology'' Oxford University Press, Oxford 1999. pp. 259\u2013260</ref> But while acknowledging the unusual shared harmonies, Dominic Pedler notes that the relationship is not the result of reversing the order of the chords as Lennon suggested.<ref>Dominic Pedler. ''The Songwriting Secrets of the Beatles''. Music Sales Limited. Omnibus Press. NY. 2003. pp. 428\u2013433</ref>\n\n\"Because\" concludes with a vocal fade-out on D[[Diminished triad|dim]], which keeps listeners in suspense as they wait for the return to the home key of C{{music|sharp}} minor. Mellers states that: \"causality is released and there is no before and no after: ''because'' that flat supertonic is a moment of revelation, it needs no resolution.\"<ref>Wilfred Mellers. ''Twilight of the Gods: The Music of the Beatles''. Schirmer/Macmillan 1973. p. 118</ref> The Ddim chord (and its accompanying melodic F{{music|natural}}) lingers until they resolve into the opening Am<sup>7</sup> chord of \"[[You Never Give Me Your Money]]\".\n\n==Recording==\nGeorge Martin on \"Because\":<ref>Buskin, Richard, insidetracks, p. 64-65</ref>\n\n{{Quote|Between us, we also created a backing track with John playing a riff on guitar, me duplicating every note on an electronic harpsichord, and Paul playing bass. Each note between the guitar and harpsichord had to be exactly together, and as I'm not the world's greatest player in terms of timing, I would make more mistakes than John did, so we had Ringo playing a regular beat on hi-hat to us through our headphones.}}\n\nThe main recording session for \"Because\" was on 1 August 1969, with vocal [[overdub]]s on 4 August, and a double-tracked Moog synthesiser overdub by Harrison on 5 August.{{sfn|Lewisohn|1988|pp=184\u2013185}} As a result, this was the last song on the album to be committed to tape, although there were still overdubs for other incomplete songs. This approach took extensive rehearsal, and more than five hours of extremely focused recording, to capture correctly. McCartney and Harrison both said it was their favourite track on ''Abbey Road''. \"They knew they were doing something special,\" said engineer [[Geoff Emerick]], \"and they were determined to get it right.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=77 \u2013 'Because'|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/100-greatest-beatles-songs-20110919/because-19691231|work=100 Greatest Beatles Songs|publisher=Rolling Stone|accessdate=17 June 2012}}</ref> \n\nA remixed version of the song, with the instrumentation removed so as to highlight the three-part harmony by Lennon, McCartney and Harrison, was released on 1996's ''[[Anthology 3]]'' and, in a different remix, on 2006's ''[[Love (Beatles album)|Love]]''. In 2016, the ''Anthology 3'' mix became the first recording by The Beatles to appear in a film trailer when it was featured in the trailer for [[Luc Besson]]'s film ''[[Valerian and the City of a Thousand Planets]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=The VALERIAN AND THE CITY OF A THOUSAND PLANETS trailer is here & Quint Talked to Luc Besson about it!|url=http://www.aintitcool.com/node/76703|publisher=Ain't It Cool News|accessdate=10 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Personnel==\n* [[John Lennon]]&nbsp;\u2013 triple-tracked harmony vocals (middle register), guitar\n* [[Paul McCartney]]&nbsp;\u2013 triple-tracked harmony vocals (high register), bass\n* [[George Harrison]]&nbsp;\u2013 triple-tracked harmony vocals (low register), [[Moog synthesizer|Moog synthesiser]]\n* [[George Martin]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[Baldwin Piano Company|Baldwin]] [[Electric piano#Other electric keyboard instruments|electric harpsichord]]\n:Personnel per [[Ian MacDonald]]{{sfn|MacDonald|2005|p=365}}\n\n==Notable cover versions==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Artist\n!Release\n!Notes\n|-\n| 1977 || [[Devo]] || ''[[The Truth About De-Evolution]]'' <small>(soundtrack)</small> || The song is heard during the film's closing credits.\n|-\n| 1978 || [[Alice Cooper]] & [[The Bee Gees]]|| ''[[Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band (soundtrack)|Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band]]'' <small>(soundtrack)</small>\n|\n|-\n| 1999 || [[Elliott Smith]] || ''[[American Beauty (1999 film)]]'' <small>(soundtrack)</small> \n|-\n| 2009 || [[Gerry Rafferty]] || ''[[Life Goes On (2009 film)|Life Goes On]]'' <small>(soundtrack)</small>\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Refbegin|2}}\n* {{cite book\n| last=Lewisohn\n| first=Mark\n| year=1988\n| authorlink=Mark Lewisohn\n| title=The Beatles Recording Sessions\n| publisher=[[Harmony Books]]\n| location=New York\n| isbn=0-517-57066-1\n| ref=harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last=MacDonald\n| first=Ian\n| year=2005\n| authorlink=Ian MacDonald\n| title=Revolution in the Head: The Beatles' Records and the Sixties\n| publisher=Pimlico (Rand)\n| location=London\n| edition=Second Revised\n| isbn=1-84413-828-3\n| ref=harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last=Miles\n| first=Barry\n| year=1997\n| authorlink=Barry Miles\n| title=Paul McCartney: Many Years From Now\n| publisher=Henry Holt & Company\n| location=New York\n| isbn=0-8050-5249-6\n| ref=harv\n| url=https://archive.org/details/paulmccartneyman00mile\n}}\n* {{cite web\n| last=Pollack\n| first=Alan W.\n| authorlink=Alan W. Pollack\n| title=Notes on \"Because\"\n| work=Notes on ... Series\n| url=http://www.icce.rug.nl/~soundscapes/DATABASES/AWP/b4.shtml\n| ref=harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last=Sheff\n| first=David\n| year=2000\n| authorlink=David Sheff\n| title=All We Are Saying\n| publisher=St. Martin's Press\n| location=New York\n| isbn=0-312-25464-4\n| ref=harv\n| url=https://archive.org/details/allwearesayingla00lenn\n}}\n* {{cite web\n| work=[[Snopes.com]]\n| year=2009\n| title=Because\n| url=http://www.snopes.com/music/songs/because.asp\n| accessdate=6 June 2009\n| ref={{SfnRef|Snopes.com|2009|pp=1}}\n}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|beatles|because}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Abbey Road}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Because (The Beatles Song)}}\n[[Category:The Beatles songs]]\n[[Category:1969 songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by George Martin]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Lennon\u2013McCartney]]\n[[Category:Alice Cooper songs]]\n[[Category:Elliott Smith songs]]\n[[Category:Negativland songs]]\n[[Category:George Clinton (musician) songs]]\n[[Category:Songs published by Northern Songs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=June 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2012}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Because\n| cover      = Because sheet music.PNG\n| cover_size = 160px\n| caption    = Cover of the song's sheet music\n| artist     = [[the Beatles]]\n| album      = [[Abbey Road]]\n| released   = {{Start date|1969|09|26|df=y}}\n| recorded   = 1\u20135 August 1969\n| studio     = [[Abbey Road Studios|EMI]], London\n| genre      = <!--- Do not add unsourced genres --->\n| length     = {{Duration|m=2|s=45}}\n| writer     = [[Lennon\u2013McCartney]]\n| label      = [[Apple Records|Apple]]\n| producer   = [[George Martin]]\n| misc       = {{Audio sample\n | type = song\n | file = Because Beatles.ogg\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Because'''\" is a song written by [[John Lennon]]{{sfn|Sheff|2000|p=191}} (credited to [[Lennon\u2013McCartney]]) and recorded by the English rock band [[the Beatles]]. It was released on their 1969 album ''[[Abbey Road]]'', immediately preceding the extended [[Medley (music)|medley]] on side two of the record. It features a prominent three-part vocal harmony by Lennon, [[Paul McCartney]], and [[George Harrison]], recorded three times to make nine voices in all.\n\n==Composition==\n[[File:Harp02.jpg|thumb|An [[electric harpsichord]] similar to the one used for \"Because\"]]\n\nThe song begins with a distinctive [[Electric piano#Other electric keyboard instruments|electric harpsichord]] intro played by producer [[George Martin]]. The harpsichord is joined by Lennon's guitar (mimicking the harpsichord line) played through a [[Leslie speaker]]. Then vocals and bass guitar enter.\n\n\"Because\" was one of few Beatles recordings to feature a [[Moog synthesizer|Moog synthesiser]], played by George Harrison. It appears in what [[Alan W. Pollack|Alan Pollack]] refers to as the \"mini-bridge\",{{sfn|Pollack}} and then again at the end of the song.\n\nAccording to Lennon, the song's close musical resemblance to the first movement of [[Ludwig van Beethoven]]'s ''[[Piano Sonata No. 14 (Beethoven)|Moonlight Sonata]]'' was no coincidence: \"[[Yoko Ono|Yoko]] was playing Beethoven's 'Moonlight Sonata' on the piano ... I said, 'Can you play those chords backwards?', and wrote 'Because' around them. The lyrics speak for themselves ... No imagery, no obscure references.\"{{sfn|Sheff|2000|p=191}}{{sfn|Snopes.com|2009|pp=1}}\n\n==Musical structure==\nWith regard to the controversy Lennon initiated by citing Beethoven's \"[[Moonlight Sonata]]\" as an inspiration,{{clarify |date=November 2017 |reason=What controversy? }} musicologist [[Walter Everett (musicologist)|Walter Everett]] notes that \"both arpeggiate triads and seventh chords in [[C-sharp minor|C{{music|sharp}} minor]] in the [[baritone]] range of a keyboard instrument at a slow tempo, move through the [[submediant]] to [[Neapolitan chord|{{music|flat}}II]] and approach [[subtonic|vii]] [[Diminished seventh chord|dim<sup>7</sup>]]/IV via a common tone.\"<ref>Walter Everett. ''The Beatles as Musicians: Revolver Through the Anthology'' Oxford University Press, Oxford 1999. pp. 259\u2013260</ref> But while acknowledging the unusual shared harmonies, Dominic Pedler notes that the relationship is not the result of reversing the order of the chords as Lennon suggested.<ref>Dominic Pedler. ''The Songwriting Secrets of the Beatles''. Music Sales Limited. Omnibus Press. NY. 2003. pp. 428\u2013433</ref>\n\n\"Because\" concludes with a vocal fade-out on D[[Diminished triad|dim]], which keeps listeners in suspense as they wait for the return to the home key of C{{music|sharp}} minor. Mellers states that: \"causality is released and there is no before and no after: ''because'' that flat supertonic is a moment of revelation, it needs no resolution.\"<ref>Wilfred Mellers. ''Twilight of the Gods: The Music of the Beatles''. Schirmer/Macmillan 1973. p. 118</ref> The Ddim chord (and its accompanying melodic F{{music|natural}}) lingers until they resolve into the opening Am<sup>7</sup> chord of \"[[You Never Give Me Your Money]]\".\n\n==Recording==\nGeorge Martin on \"Because\":<ref>Buskin, Richard, insidetracks, p. 64-65</ref>\n\n{{Quote|Between us, we also created a backing track with John playing a riff on guitar, me duplicating every note on an electronic harpsichord, and Paul playing bass. Each note between the guitar and harpsichord had to be exactly together, and as I'm not the world's greatest player in terms of timing, I would make more mistakes than John did, so we had Ringo playing a regular beat on hi-hat to us through our headphones.}}\n\nThe main recording session for \"Because\" was on 1 August 1969, with vocal [[overdub]]s on 4 August, and a double-tracked Moog synthesiser overdub by Harrison on 5 August.{{sfn|Lewisohn|1988|pp=184\u2013185}} As a result, this was the last song on the album to be committed to tape, although there were still overdubs for other incomplete songs. This approach took extensive rehearsal, and more than five hours of extremely focused recording, to capture correctly. McCartney and Harrison both said it was their favourite track on ''Abbey Road''. \"They knew they were doing something special,\" said engineer [[Geoff Emerick]], \"and they were determined to get it right.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=77 \u2013 'Because'|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/100-greatest-beatles-songs-20110919/because-19691231|work=100 Greatest Beatles Songs|publisher=Rolling Stone|accessdate=17 June 2012}}</ref> \n\nA remixed version of the song, with the instrumentation removed so as to highlight the three-part harmony by Lennon, McCartney and Harrison, was released on 1996's ''[[Anthology 3]]'' and, in a different remix, on 2006's ''[[Love (Beatles album)|Love]]''. In 2016, the ''Anthology 3'' mix became the first recording by The Beatles to appear in a film trailer when it was featured in the trailer for [[Luc Besson]]'s film ''[[Valerian and the City of a Thousand Planets]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=The VALERIAN AND THE CITY OF A THOUSAND PLANETS trailer is here & Quint Talked to Luc Besson about it!|url=http://www.aintitcool.com/node/76703|publisher=Ain't It Cool News|accessdate=10 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Personnel==\n* [[John Lennon]]&nbsp;\u2013 triple-tracked harmony vocals (middle register), guitar\n* [[Paul McCartney]]&nbsp;\u2013 triple-tracked harmony vocals (high register), bass\n* [[George Harrison]]&nbsp;\u2013 triple-tracked harmony vocals (low register), [[Moog synthesizer|Moog synthesiser]]\n* [[George Martin]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[Baldwin Piano Company|Baldwin]] [[Electric piano#Other electric keyboard instruments|electric harpsichord]]\n:Personnel per [[Ian MacDonald]]{{sfn|MacDonald|2005|p=365}}\n\n==Notable cover versions==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Artist\n!Release\n!Notes\n|-\n| 1977 || [[Devo]] || ''[[The Truth About De-Evolution]]'' <small>(soundtrack)</small> || The song is heard during the film's closing credits.\n|-\n| 1978 || [[Alice Cooper]] & [[The Bee Gees]]|| ''[[Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band (soundtrack)|Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band]]'' <small>(soundtrack)</small>\n|\n|-\n| 1999 || [[Elliott Smith]] || ''[[American Beauty (1999 film)]]'' <small>(soundtrack)</small> \n|-\n| 2009 || [[Gerry Rafferty]] || ''[[Life Goes On]]'' <small>(soundtrack)</small>\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Refbegin|2}}\n* {{cite book\n| last=Lewisohn\n| first=Mark\n| year=1988\n| authorlink=Mark Lewisohn\n| title=The Beatles Recording Sessions\n| publisher=[[Harmony Books]]\n| location=New York\n| isbn=0-517-57066-1\n| ref=harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last=MacDonald\n| first=Ian\n| year=2005\n| authorlink=Ian MacDonald\n| title=Revolution in the Head: The Beatles' Records and the Sixties\n| publisher=Pimlico (Rand)\n| location=London\n| edition=Second Revised\n| isbn=1-84413-828-3\n| ref=harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last=Miles\n| first=Barry\n| year=1997\n| authorlink=Barry Miles\n| title=Paul McCartney: Many Years From Now\n| publisher=Henry Holt & Company\n| location=New York\n| isbn=0-8050-5249-6\n| ref=harv\n| url=https://archive.org/details/paulmccartneyman00mile\n}}\n* {{cite web\n| last=Pollack\n| first=Alan W.\n| authorlink=Alan W. Pollack\n| title=Notes on \"Because\"\n| work=Notes on ... Series\n| url=http://www.icce.rug.nl/~soundscapes/DATABASES/AWP/b4.shtml\n| ref=harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last=Sheff\n| first=David\n| year=2000\n| authorlink=David Sheff\n| title=All We Are Saying\n| publisher=St. Martin's Press\n| location=New York\n| isbn=0-312-25464-4\n| ref=harv\n| url=https://archive.org/details/allwearesayingla00lenn\n}}\n* {{cite web\n| work=[[Snopes.com]]\n| year=2009\n| title=Because\n| url=http://www.snopes.com/music/songs/because.asp\n| accessdate=6 June 2009\n| ref={{SfnRef|Snopes.com|2009|pp=1}}\n}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|beatles|because}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Abbey Road}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Because (The Beatles Song)}}\n[[Category:The Beatles songs]]\n[[Category:1969 songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by George Martin]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Lennon\u2013McCartney]]\n[[Category:Alice Cooper songs]]\n[[Category:Elliott Smith songs]]\n[[Category:Negativland songs]]\n[[Category:George Clinton (musician) songs]]\n[[Category:Songs published by Northern Songs]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toLife Goes On(link changed toLife Goes On (2009 film)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Because_(Beatles_song)"}
{"title_page": "Blueberry Faygo", "text_new": "{{short description|2020 single by Lil Mosey}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Blueberry Faygo\n| type       = single\n| cover      = Lil Mosey - Blueberry Faygo.png\n| artist     = [[Lil Mosey]]\n| album      = [[Certified Hitmaker|Certified Hitmaker (reissue)]]\n| released   = {{start date|2020|2|7|mf=y}}\n| recorded   =\n| format     = {{hlist|[[Music download|Digital download]]|[[Streaming media|streaming]]}}\n| genre      =\n| length     = {{duration|m=2|s=43}}\n| label      = {{hlist|[[Interscope Records|Interscope]]|Mogul Vision}}\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[Lil Mosey|Lathan Echols]]|[[Johnny Gill|Johnny Gill, Jr.]]|[[L.A. Reid|Antonio Reid]]|[[Babyface (musician)|Kenneth Edmonds]]|Callan Wong}}\n| producer   = Callan\n| chronology = [[Lil Mosey]]\n| prev_title = [[Stuck in a Dream]]\n| prev_year  = 2019\n| title      = Blueberry Faygo\n| year       = 2020\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|V_jHc_n0p9c|\"Blueberry Faygo\"}}}}\n}}\n\"'''Blueberry Faygo'''\" is a single by American rapper [[Lil Mosey]]. It was released on February 7, 2020, by [[Interscope Records]] and Mogul Vision Music. It was released concurrently with the reissue of his second [[studio album]] ''[[Certified Hitmaker]]'' (2019), which the single appears on.<ref>https://listen.tidal.com/album/131891266/credits</ref>\n\n==Background==\nIn late 2019, a leaked upload of the track on [[Spotify]] reached 21 million streams before it was taken down.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/lil-mosey-blueberry-faygo-945083/|title='We Can't Stop These Kids At All': The Curious Case of a Leaked Hit|last=Leight|first=Elias|date=2020-02-04|website=[[Rolling Stone]]|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref> It was followed by numerous others, causing the song to go viral before it was officially released on February 7, 2020.<ref name=\"DX\">{{Cite web|url=https://hiphopdx.com/news/id.54469/title.lil-mosey-gets-a-head-start-on-summer-2020-with-blueberry-faygo-single|title=Lil Mosey Gets A Head Start On Summer 2020 With 'Blueberry Faygo' Single|last=|first=|date=2020-02-08|website=[[HipHopDX]]|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref> It became Lil Mosey's most successful single to date after being picked up by [[TikTok]] users for dance challenges.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elitedaily.com/p/12-viral-tiktok-songs-youll-never-ever-get-sick-of-listening-to-22414496|title=12 Songs That Went Viral On TikTok, Because They Never, Ever Get Old|website=[[Elite Daily]]|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref>\n\n\"Blueberry Faygo\" was produced by Callan and samples \"[[My, My, My (Johnny Gill song)|My, My, My]]\" by American singer-songwriter [[Johnny Gill]].<ref name=\"DX\" />\n\n==Music video==\nThe song's official music video was released on March 26, 2020.<ref>{{Citation|title=Lil Mosey - Blueberry Faygo (Dir. by @_ColeBennett_)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=V_jHc_n0p9c|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> It was released through music video director, [[Cole Bennett]]'s YouTube channel. The video features appearances from Australian rapper [[The Kid Laroi]] and [[TikTok]] stars [[Addison Rae]] & Lil Huddy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/9343752/lil-mosey-blueberry-faygo-video|title=Lil Mosey&#39;s &#39;Blueberry Faygo&#39; Video: Watch|date=2020-03-26|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\nThe music video was filmed at the Hype House, a TikTok mansion in Los Angeles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2020/03/lil-mosey-blueberry-faygo|title=Watch Lil Mosey's \"Blueberry Faygo\" Video|website=Complex|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n==Chart performance==\n\"Blueberry Faygo\" debuted at number 62 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], tying with Mosey's previous single \"[[Stuck in a Dream]]\", his highest-charting single before.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/lyrics/8551828/lil-mosey-blueberry-faygo-lyrics|title=Lil Mosey's 'Blueberry Faygo' Lyrics|date=2020-02-24|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref> It later surpassed \"Stuck in a Dream\", peaking at number 18, becoming Mosey's first top 20. \n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2020)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Australia ([[ARIA Charts|ARIA]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ariacharts.com.au/charts/singles-chart|title=ARIA Australian Top 50 Singles|publisher=[[Australian Recording Industry Association]]|date=April 13, 2020|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n| 17\n|-\n{{single chart|Austria|37|artist=Lil Mosey|song=Blueberry Faygo|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Flanders Tip|2|artist=Lil Mosey|song=Blueberry Faygo|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 17, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Wallonia Tip|11|artist=Lil Mosey|song=Blueberry Faygo|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 17, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Canada|8|artist=Lil Mosey|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 7, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Czechdigital|17|year=2020|week=15|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 15, 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Denmark ([[Tracklisten]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hitlisten.nu/default.asp?w=14&y=2020&list=t40|title=Track Top-40 Uge 14, 2020|publisher=[[Hitlisten]]|accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n| 19\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Estonia ([[Eesti Tipp-40]])<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ekspress.delfi.ee/areen/eesti-tipp-40-muusikas-sel-nadalal-paugutab-tradattack?id=89544845|title=Eesti Tipp-40 Muusikas: Sel n\u00e4dalal paugutab Trad.Attack!|language=Estonian|last=Nestor|first=Siim|website=[[Eesti Ekspress]]|date=April 14, 2020|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n| 6\n|-\n{{single chart|Finland|16|artist=Lil Mosey|song=Blueberry Faygo|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| France ([[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|