fe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCharts:updated", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blueberry_Faygo"}
{"title_page": "Harvey Wippleman", "text_new": "{{short description|American professional wrestling manager, referee and wrestler}}\n{{Infobox professional wrestler\n| name        = Harvey Wippleman\n| image       = Wippleman20020316.jpg\n| caption     = Harvey Wippleman in March 2002\n| birth_name  = Bruno Lauer\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1965|10|27|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = Mississippi [[United States]]<ref name=slam/>\n| resides     =\n| names       = Bruno<br>Dr. Lennerd Spazzinsky<br>Downtown Bruno<br>'''Harvey Wippleman''' <br>Handsome Harvey<br>Hervina<br>Uptown Bruno\n| height      =\n| weight      =\n| billed      = [[Walls, Mississippi]]<ref name=encyclopedia>{{cite book|title=WWE Encyclopedia|author=Shields, Brian and Kevin Sullivan|publisher=DK/BradyGAMES|year=2009|isbn=978-0-7566-4190-0|page=[https://archive.org/details/wweencyclopediad0000shie/page/126 126]|url=https://archive.org/details/wweencyclopediad0000shie/page/126}}</ref>\n| trainer     = [[Geeto Mongol]]<ref name=slam/>\n| debut       = 1979<ref name=slam/>\n| retired     = \n}}\n'''Bruno Lauer''' (born October 27, 1965) is an American [[professional wrestling]] [[Manager (professional wrestling)|manager]], [[Referee (professional wrestling)|referee]], and occasional wrestler, better known by his [[ring name]]s, '''Harvey Wippleman''' and '''Downtown Bruno'''.\n\nWippleman began his career working in [[professional wrestling promotion]]s in the Southern United States, especially [[Memphis, Tennessee|Memphis]]. In the 1990s, he debuted in the [[WWE|World Wrestling Federation]] (WWF), where he managed wrestlers such as [[Sid Eudy|Sid Justice]], [[Kamala (wrestler)|Kamala]], [[Giant Gonzalez]] and [[Rhonda Sing|Bertha Faye]]. In 2000, he became the first and only man to win the [[WWE Women's Championship (1956\u20132010)|WWF Women's Championship]]. Wippleman works backstage in WWE (formerly the WWF) and occasionally manages in the Memphis area as Downtown Bruno.\n\nThe difference between Harry Potter and the Jews: Harry Potter survived the Chambers.\n\n==Professional wrestling career==\n\n===Early career===\nIn 1979, Lauer attended an [[independent circuit|independent wrestling show]] at a [[circus]] in [[Pennsylvania]].<ref name=slam/> In exchange for helping to tear down the ring after the show, he was given free admission.<ref name=slam/> He later joined the company and toured Ohio.<ref name=slam/> During this time, [[The Royal Kangaroos]]' [[Jonathan Boyd]] became his mentor.<ref name=slam/> Back in Pennsylvania, [[Geeto Mongol]] trained Lauer and gave him the ring name Dr. Lennerd Spazzinsky.<ref name=slam/>\n\nHe then moved to Memphis, where he performed under the name Downtown Bruno.<ref name=slam/><ref name=rmn>{{cite news|url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/news/2008/jul/24/wrestling-outside-the-ring-lauer-a-perfect/|title=Wrestling: Outside the ring, Lauer a perfect 'concierge'|newspaper=Rocky Mountain News|last=Marvez|first=Alex|date=2008-07-24|accessdate=2009-08-06}}</ref> In 1986, he became the most prominent [[Heel (professional wrestling)|villainous]] manager in Memphis.<ref name=slam/> In addition, wrestlers like [[Jerry Lawler]] and [[Sid Eudy]] helped his career.<ref name=slam/> He continued to work in the Southern promotions for the rest of the late 1980s.<ref name=slam/> In September 1989, he won the [[Continental Championship Wrestling|Continental Wrestling Federation]]'s [[NWA Southeastern United States Junior Heavyweight Championship|Southeastern United States Junior Heavyweight Championship]] and held it until the promotion closed in November. It was in Continental in 1987 that he first teamed with Eudy, while Eudy was under a mask as an incarnation of Lord Humongous.<ref name=\"Titles\">{{cite book|author=Duncan, Royal and Gary Will|title=Wrestling Title Histories|publisher=Archeus Communications|year=2006|edition=4th|isbn=0-9698161-5-4}}</ref>\n\n===World Wrestling Federation/Entertainment===\n\n====Manager====\n[[File:Harvey Wippleman in 1994.jpg|thumb|right|Harvey Wippleman as a manager in 1994]]\nIn 1991, Sid Eudy helped bring Lauer to the [[World Wrestling Entertainment|World Wrestling Federation]] (WWF).<ref name=slam/><ref name=rmn/> He debuted as Harvey Wippleman, a Pee-Wee Herman-like character wearing a pin-striped suit with slacks cut at his shins, a red bow-tie, and a [[flat cap]].  He first managed [[Nick Busick|Big Bully Busick]].<ref name=west>{{cite news|url=http://www.timeswv.com/wvu_sports/local_story_125232306.html|title=WVU football recruit Busick will wrestle as well|author=Hertzel, Bob|newspaper=The Times West Virginian|date=May 5, 2009|accessdate=2009-05-07|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130204095101/http://www.timeswv.com/wvu_sports/local_story_125232306.html|archivedate=February 4, 2013}}</ref>  When Busick left the company and Slick turned face, Wippleman took over managing The Warlord.  However, Wippleman's greatest acquisition was his real-life friend, Sid Justice. When Sid turned heel, working on a program with Hulk Hogan leading to Wrestlemania, Wippleman became Sid Justice's manager and became \"Dr. Harvey Wippleman\".  Wippleman would begin carrying a doctor's bag to the ring containing medical equipment.  After Sid's matches against jobbers, Wippleman would retrieve a stethoscope from his bag and listen to the defeated wrestler's hearts.\n\nAfter Sid left the company, Wippleman managed [[Kamala (wrestler)|Kamala]], who was [[feud (professional wrestling)|feuding]] with [[The Undertaker]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Kamala's bio|accessdate=2008-09-16|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|url=http://www.wwe.com/superstars/wwealumni/kamala/bio/}}</ref> After Kamala was defeated by Undertaker in a [[Professional wrestling match types#Container-based variations|Coffin match]] at [[Survivor Series (1992)|Survivor Series]] in 1992, Kamala left Wippleman and [[Slick (wrestling)|Reverend Slick]] became his new manager.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kamala Matata|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|date=2007-05-28|first=Mike|last=McAvennie|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/listthis/wildestsuperstars/wildestsuperstars3|accessdate=2008-09-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=From Season to Season: Sports as American Religion|author=Price, Joseph L.|publisher=Mercer University Press|year=2005|isbn=0-86554-961-3|page=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_2900865549615/page/209 209]|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_2900865549615/page/209}}</ref> Afterwards, Wippleman dropped the Dr. gimmick. He continued to feud with the Undertaker and brought a new wrestler to the WWF, the nearly eight-foot-tall [[Jorge Gonz\u00e1lez (wrestler)|Giant Gonz\u00e1lez]]. The feud culminated in a [[No Disqualification match|Rest in Peace match]] at [[SummerSlam (1993)|SummerSlam]], which Undertaker won.<ref name=wwequizbook-pp85>{{cite book|last=Feigenbaum|first=Aaron|author2=Kevin Kelly |author3=Seth Mates |author4=Brian Solomon |author5=Phil Speer |title=The Ultimate World Wrestling Entertainment Trivia Book|page=85|isbn=0-7434-5756-0}}</ref>  During this period, Wippleman also briefly managed Mr. Hughes, who left the WWF after a few months. Wippleman was also the manager of [[Bryan Clark|Adam Bomb]] from October 1993 until June 1994, when Bomb turned face, and feuded with [[Savio Vega|Kwang]], who was also being managed by Wippleman. Wippleman also managed [[Well Dunn]], who faced the [[The Rock 'n' Roll Express|Rock 'n' Roll Express]] in the RnR's WWF debut on October 10, 1993.<ref>{{Citation|last=Top Turnbuckle|title=Rock N' Roll Express vs. Well Dunn (10-10-1993)|date=2015-03-28|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sxmFAnu4MI0|accessdate=2018-01-06}}</ref>\n\nSince debuting in the WWF, Wippleman was always at odds with ring announcer [[Howard Finkel]], whom Wippleman believed introduced him in a condescending manner. At [[WrestleMania X]], Wippleman tore up Finkel's tuxedo, and Finkel shoved him to the mat. The feud culminated in a [[Professional wrestling match types#Tuxedo match|tuxedo match]] on the January 9, 1995 edition of ''[[WWE Raw|Monday Night RAW]]'', which Finkel won.<ref name=legacy>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/subscriptions/legacy/19901995/|title=Matches from the early 1990s|accessdate=2009-05-07|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090305224033/http://www.wwe.com/subscriptions/legacy/19901995/|archivedate=March 5, 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nWippleman's next high-profile storyline was later in 1995, when he managed his on-screen girlfriend [[Rhonda Sing|Bertha Faye]].<ref name=encyclopedia/><ref name=list>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/listthis/greatestwhoamances/greatwhoamances9|title=List This #9: Harvey's whipped|author=McAvennie, Mike|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=2008-09-23|date=February 15, 2007}}</ref> Faye, with Wippleman in her corner, won the [[WWE Women's Championship (1956\u20132010)|WWF Women's Championship]] by defeating [[Debrah Miceli|Alundra Blayze]] at [[SummerSlam (1995)|SummerSlam 1995]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/women/304454132121112115|title=Bertha Faye's reign|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=2008-08-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated: 2008 Wrestling Almanac & Book of Facts|publisher=Sports & Entertainment Publications, LLC|issn=1043-7576|volume=29|issue=5|page=123}}</ref> After losing the WWF Women's Championship in late 1995, Faye was dropped from the WWF roster and Wippleman disappeared from television. According to Lauer, he and Bertha didn't get along.<ref>{{Citation|last=OWWRadio|title=OWW Radio Ep. 6 - Harvey Whippleman Part 5/6|date=2009-04-04|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=x7FSa5fhNcE|accessdate=2018-01-06}}</ref>\n\n====Referee and road agent====\nBy spring 1996, Wippleman began making appearances on ''[[WWF Superstars of Wrestling|WWF Superstars]]'', critiquing the referees during the matches in preparation to make a full report to WWF President [[Gorilla Monsoon]] about the apparent lack of consistency amongst the officials. Monsoon rewarded Wippleman for his efforts by making him an official referee. One of Wippleman's last appearances as a regular WWF referee during this time came on the March 10, 1997 episode of ''Raw'' when [[Joanie Laurer|Chyna]] [[Gorilla press slam|gorilla press]]ed him into a group of referees.\nOn the May 19, 1997 episode  of ''Raw'' Wippleman appeared in a backstage segment with [[Stone Cold Steve Austin]] telling Wippleman that he was going to be his tag team partner with Wippleman responding that he was scared. Wippleman also appeared as \"Handsome Harvey,\" introducing D-Generation-X on ''Raw'' on November 24, 1997. This was to make fun of [[Rick Rude]]. Rude had been a member of DX and had just left the company a week earlier to go to WCW. This resulted in Rude being on both ''Raw'' and ''WCW Monday Nitro'' on the same night. (At the time, ''Raw'' was taped every other week while ''Nitro'' was live every week).\n\nIn June 1999, after another period of absence from television broadcasts, Wippleman resurfaced on the June 13 episode of ''Sunday Night Heat'' as a referee in a match between then-Intercontinental Champion [[Jeff Jarrett]] and [[Test (wrestler)|Test]].  Test won the match after outside interference, thus being named the new champion, but he was persuaded by Jarrett's valet [[Debra Marshall|Debra]] to overturn the result and return the belt.  He also served as a [[Strikebreaker|scab]] official during the WWF referee strike in September 1999, including at the [[Unforgiven (1999)|Unforgiven]] PPV, again refereeing a match with Jarrett defending the Intercontinental title against Chyna.\n\nOn January 31, 2000, Wippleman won the WWF Women's Championship from [[Stacy Carter|The Kat]] while he was in a disguise and used the name \"Hervina\" in a \"Lumberjill Snow Bunny\" match, which took place in a snow-filled pool surrounded by female wrestlers who kept the competitors from leaving the pool.<ref name=encyclopedia/><ref name=women>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/women/304454132121112213|title=Women's Title History: Hervina|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=2009-05-06}}</ref> The win made him the first male to hold the Women's Championship.<ref name=women/> He lost the title the following day (but broadcast on February 3) to Jacqueline in a match that lasted under a minute,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/women/30445413212111216|title=Women's Title History: Jacqueline|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=2009-05-06}}</ref> thus ending the shortest reign in the title's history.  Through the remainder of 2000, Wippleman appeared in backstage and non-match segments of the WWF's television programming, including a segment on the April 23, 2000 episode of ''Sunday Night Heat'' where he appeared dressed up as a rabbit as part of a segment with [[Al Snow]] and [[Steve Blackman]].\n\nAt [[WrestleMania X-Seven]] on April 1, 2001, Wippleman managed Kamala during the gimmick battle royal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=INFC7xG77mI|title=Gimmick Battle Royal - WrestleMania X-Seven\n| publisher = YouTube |accessdate=January 17, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAt the point the [[The Invasion (professional wrestling)|Invasion storyline]] began in 2001, he had disappeared from WWF programming, and was then working as a [[List of professional wrestling terms#A|road agent]] for the company.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://morningjournal.com/articles/2008/07/27/sports/19871326.txt|title=Off the Turnbuckle: Raw-ECW merger plans have been scrapped|last=Gilles|first=Dan|newspaper=The Morning Journal|accessdate=2009-05-06|date=2008-07-27|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120218151953/http://morningjournal.com/articles/2008/07/27/sports/19871326.txt|archivedate=2012-02-18}}</ref>\n\nOn November 15, 2010, for WWE's old school episode of ''Raw'', Wippleman returned to WWE, managing the [[Brooklyn Brawler]] in a squash loss to Ezekiel Jackson.\n\nAs of 2011, Lauer was working with the WWE in backstage roles at television and pay-per-view events.  In an interview with [[Jim Korderas]], Lauer described his role as \"concierge\", taking care of details such as food, rental cars and the like.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://radio.thescore.com/episodes/harvey-whippleman-nov-10-2011|title=Harvey Whippleman - Nov 10, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20111114140835/http://radio.thescore.com/episodes/harvey-whippleman-nov-10-2011|archivedate=2011-11-14}}</ref>\n\nOn January 22, 2018, Harvey made a brief backstage appearance during [[Raw 25 Years]].\n\n==Personal life==\nLauer grew up in [[Penn Hills, Pennsylvania]], near [[Pittsburgh]].<ref name=rmn/> According to Lauer, he spent his teenage years \"sprawling on car hoods, smoking cigarettes, and drinking beer with no particular ambition in mind\".<ref name=slam/> His drinking eventually caused Lauer to serve jail time in Memphis.<ref name=slam/>\n\nIn 1994, Lauer was in a car accident with [[Joey Marella]], which claimed Marella's life and injured Lauer.<ref name=slam/> The crash occurred as a result of Marella falling asleep at the wheel while driving on the way to [[Newark, New Jersey|Newark]].<ref name=moon/> Marella was not wearing his seat belt, but Lauer\u2013the passenger\u2013was wearing his.<ref name=moon>{{cite web|url=http://www.mikemooneyham.com/pages/viewfull.cfm?ObjectID=B9F6BD0A-2627-4FE4-B3801B91D574CE58|title=Crash Claims Joey Marella|author=Mooneyham, Mike|publisher=The Wrestling Gospel|date=1994-07-10|accessdate=2009-05-07|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081113123415/http://www.mikemooneyham.com/pages/viewfull.cfm?ObjectID=B9F6BD0A-2627-4FE4-B3801B91D574CE58|archivedate=November 13, 2008}}</ref> Because of the severity of his injuries, however, Lauer incurred approximately $10,000 in medical expenses.<ref name=slam/> He wrote an autobiography ''Wrestling with the Truth'', which was released in 2008.<ref name=slam>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/Reviews/2008/08/13/6436746.html|title=Lauer's book a good glimpse at a day gone by|author=Johnson, Steven|date=August 19, 2008|accessdate=2009-05-07}}</ref><ref name=rmn/> Lauer is [[Roman Catholic]].\n\n==Championships and accomplishments==\n'''[[Continental Championship Wrestling|Continental Wrestling Federation]]'''\n*[[NWA Southeastern United States Junior Heavyweight Championship|Southeast United States Junior Heavyweight Championship]] (1 time)<ref name=\"Titles\"/>\n\n'''[[World Wrestling Entertainment|World Wrestling Federation]]'''\n*[[WWE Women's Championship (1956\u20132010)|WWF Women's Championship]] ([[List of WWE Women's Champions|1 time]])<ref name=women/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Professional wrestling profiles}}\n{{WWE Women's Championship}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wippleman, Harvey}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:American male professional wrestlers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:People from Walls, Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestling managers and valets]]\n[[Category:WWF/WWE Women's Champions]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American professional wrestling manager, referee and wrestler}}\n{{Infobox professional wrestler\n| name        = Harvey Wippleman\n| image       = Wippleman20020316.jpg\n| caption     = Harvey Wippleman in March 2002\n| birth_name  = Bruno Lauer\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1965|10|27|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = Mississippi [[United States]]<ref name=slam/>\n| resides     =\n| names       = Bruno<br>Dr. Lennerd Spazzinsky<br>Downtown Bruno<br>'''Harvey Wippleman''' <br>Handsome Harvey<br>Hervina<br>Uptown Bruno\n| height      =\n| weight      =\n| billed      = [[Walls, Mississippi]]<ref name=encyclopedia>{{cite book|title=WWE Encyclopedia|author=Shields, Brian and Kevin Sullivan|publisher=DK/BradyGAMES|year=2009|isbn=978-0-7566-4190-0|page=[https://archive.org/details/wweencyclopediad0000shie/page/126 126]|url=https://archive.org/details/wweencyclopediad0000shie/page/126}}</ref>\n| trainer     = [[Geeto Mongol]]<ref name=slam/>\n| debut       = 1979<ref name=slam/>\n| retired     = \n}}\n'''Bruno Lauer''' (born October 27, 1965) is an American [[professional wrestling]] [[Manager (professional wrestling)|manager]], [[Referee (professional wrestling)|referee]], and occasional wrestler, better known by his [[ring name]]s, '''Harvey Wippleman''' and '''Downtown Bruno'''.\n\nWippleman began his career working in [[professional wrestling promotion]]s in the Southern United States, especially [[Memphis, Tennessee|Memphis]]. In the 1990s, he debuted in the [[WWE|World Wrestling Federation]] (WWF), where he managed wrestlers such as [[Sid Eudy|Sid Justice]], [[Kamala (wrestler)|Kamala]], [[Giant Gonzalez]] and [[Rhonda Sing|Bertha Faye]]. In 2000, he became the first and only man to win the [[WWE Women's Championship (1956\u20132010)|WWF Women's Championship]]. Wippleman works backstage in WWE (formerly the WWF) and occasionally manages in the Memphis area as Downtown Bruno.\n\n==Professional wrestling career==\n\n===Early career===\nIn 1979, Lauer attended an [[independent circuit|independent wrestling show]] at a [[circus]] in [[Pennsylvania]].<ref name=slam/> In exchange for helping to tear down the ring after the show, he was given free admission.<ref name=slam/> He later joined the company and toured Ohio.<ref name=slam/> During this time, [[The Royal Kangaroos]]' [[Jonathan Boyd]] became his mentor.<ref name=slam/> Back in Pennsylvania, [[Geeto Mongol]] trained Lauer and gave him the ring name Dr. Lennerd Spazzinsky.<ref name=slam/>\n\nHe then moved to Memphis, where he performed under the name Downtown Bruno.<ref name=slam/><ref name=rmn>{{cite news|url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/news/2008/jul/24/wrestling-outside-the-ring-lauer-a-perfect/|title=Wrestling: Outside the ring, Lauer a perfect 'concierge'|newspaper=Rocky Mountain News|last=Marvez|first=Alex|date=2008-07-24|accessdate=2009-08-06}}</ref> In 1986, he became the most prominent [[Heel (professional wrestling)|villainous]] manager in Memphis.<ref name=slam/> In addition, wrestlers like [[Jerry Lawler]] and [[Sid Eudy]] helped his career.<ref name=slam/> He continued to work in the Southern promotions for the rest of the late 1980s.<ref name=slam/> In September 1989, he won the [[Continental Championship Wrestling|Continental Wrestling Federation]]'s [[NWA Southeastern United States Junior Heavyweight Championship|Southeastern United States Junior Heavyweight Championship]] and held it until the promotion closed in November. It was in Continental in 1987 that he first teamed with Eudy, while Eudy was under a mask as an incarnation of Lord Humongous.<ref name=\"Titles\">{{cite book|author=Duncan, Royal and Gary Will|title=Wrestling Title Histories|publisher=Archeus Communications|year=2006|edition=4th|isbn=0-9698161-5-4}}</ref>\n\n===World Wrestling Federation/Entertainment===\n\n====Manager====\n[[File:Harvey Wippleman in 1994.jpg|thumb|right|Harvey Wippleman as a manager in 1994]]\nIn 1991, Sid Eudy helped bring Lauer to the [[World Wrestling Entertainment|World Wrestling Federation]] (WWF).<ref name=slam/><ref name=rmn/> He debuted as Harvey Wippleman, a Pee-Wee Herman-like character wearing a pin-striped suit with slacks cut at his shins, a red bow-tie, and a [[flat cap]].  He first managed [[Nick Busick|Big Bully Busick]].<ref name=west>{{cite news|url=http://www.timeswv.com/wvu_sports/local_story_125232306.html|title=WVU football recruit Busick will wrestle as well|author=Hertzel, Bob|newspaper=The Times West Virginian|date=May 5, 2009|accessdate=2009-05-07|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130204095101/http://www.timeswv.com/wvu_sports/local_story_125232306.html|archivedate=February 4, 2013}}</ref>  When Busick left the company and Slick turned face, Wippleman took over managing The Warlord.  However, Wippleman's greatest acquisition was his real-life friend, Sid Justice. When Sid turned heel, working on a program with Hulk Hogan leading to Wrestlemania, Wippleman became Sid Justice's manager and became \"Dr. Harvey Wippleman\".  Wippleman would begin carrying a doctor's bag to the ring containing medical equipment.  After Sid's matches against jobbers, Wippleman would retrieve a stethoscope from his bag and listen to the defeated wrestler's hearts.\n\nAfter Sid left the company, Wippleman managed [[Kamala (wrestler)|Kamala]], who was [[feud (professional wrestling)|feuding]] with [[The Undertaker]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Kamala's bio|accessdate=2008-09-16|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|url=http://www.wwe.com/superstars/wwealumni/kamala/bio/}}</ref> After Kamala was defeated by Undertaker in a [[Professional wrestling match types#Container-based variations|Coffin match]] at [[Survivor Series (1992)|Survivor Series]] in 1992, Kamala left Wippleman and [[Slick (wrestling)|Reverend Slick]] became his new manager.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kamala Matata|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|date=2007-05-28|first=Mike|last=McAvennie|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/listthis/wildestsuperstars/wildestsuperstars3|accessdate=2008-09-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=From Season to Season: Sports as American Religion|author=Price, Joseph L.|publisher=Mercer University Press|year=2005|isbn=0-86554-961-3|page=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_2900865549615/page/209 209]|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_2900865549615/page/209}}</ref> Afterwards, Wippleman dropped the Dr. gimmick. He continued to feud with the Undertaker and brought a new wrestler to the WWF, the nearly eight-foot-tall [[Jorge Gonz\u00e1lez (wrestler)|Giant Gonz\u00e1lez]]. The feud culminated in a [[No Disqualification match|Rest in Peace match]] at [[SummerSlam (1993)|SummerSlam]], which Undertaker won.<ref name=wwequizbook-pp85>{{cite book|last=Feigenbaum|first=Aaron|author2=Kevin Kelly |author3=Seth Mates |author4=Brian Solomon |author5=Phil Speer |title=The Ultimate World Wrestling Entertainment Trivia Book|page=85|isbn=0-7434-5756-0}}</ref>  During this period, Wippleman also briefly managed Mr. Hughes, who left the WWF after a few months. Wippleman was also the manager of [[Bryan Clark|Adam Bomb]] from October 1993 until June 1994, when Bomb turned face, and feuded with [[Savio Vega|Kwang]], who was also being managed by Wippleman. Wippleman also managed [[Well Dunn]], who faced the [[The Rock 'n' Roll Express|Rock 'n' Roll Express]] in the RnR's WWF debut on October 10, 1993.<ref>{{Citation|last=Top Turnbuckle|title=Rock N' Roll Express vs. Well Dunn (10-10-1993)|date=2015-03-28|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sxmFAnu4MI0|accessdate=2018-01-06}}</ref>\n\nSince debuting in the WWF, Wippleman was always at odds with ring announcer [[Howard Finkel]], whom Wippleman believed introduced him in a condescending manner. At [[WrestleMania X]], Wippleman tore up Finkel's tuxedo, and Finkel shoved him to the mat. The feud culminated in a [[Professional wrestling match types#Tuxedo match|tuxedo match]] on the January 9, 1995 edition of ''[[WWE Raw|Monday Night RAW]]'', which Finkel won.<ref name=legacy>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/subscriptions/legacy/19901995/|title=Matches from the early 1990s|accessdate=2009-05-07|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090305224033/http://www.wwe.com/subscriptions/legacy/19901995/|archivedate=March 5, 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nWippleman's next high-profile storyline was later in 1995, when he managed his on-screen girlfriend [[Rhonda Sing|Bertha Faye]].<ref name=encyclopedia/><ref name=list>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/listthis/greatestwhoamances/greatwhoamances9|title=List This #9: Harvey's whipped|author=McAvennie, Mike|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=2008-09-23|date=February 15, 2007}}</ref> Faye, with Wippleman in her corner, won the [[WWE Women's Championship (1956\u20132010)|WWF Women's Championship]] by defeating [[Debrah Miceli|Alundra Blayze]] at [[SummerSlam (1995)|SummerSlam 1995]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/women/304454132121112115|title=Bertha Faye's reign|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=2008-08-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated: 2008 Wrestling Almanac & Book of Facts|publisher=Sports & Entertainment Publications, LLC|issn=1043-7576|volume=29|issue=5|page=123}}</ref> After losing the WWF Women's Championship in late 1995, Faye was dropped from the WWF roster and Wippleman disappeared from television. According to Lauer, he and Bertha didn't get along.<ref>{{Citation|last=OWWRadio|title=OWW Radio Ep. 6 - Harvey Whippleman Part 5/6|date=2009-04-04|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=x7FSa5fhNcE|accessdate=2018-01-06}}</ref>\n\n====Referee and road agent====\nBy spring 1996, Wippleman began making appearances on ''[[WWF Superstars of Wrestling|WWF Superstars]]'', critiquing the referees during the matches in preparation to make a full report to WWF President [[Gorilla Monsoon]] about the apparent lack of consistency amongst the officials. Monsoon rewarded Wippleman for his efforts by making him an official referee. One of Wippleman's last appearances as a regular WWF referee during this time came on the March 10, 1997 episode of ''Raw'' when [[Joanie Laurer|Chyna]] [[Gorilla press slam|gorilla press]]ed him into a group of referees.\nOn the May 19, 1997 episode  of ''Raw'' Wippleman appeared in a backstage segment with [[Stone Cold Steve Austin]] telling Wippleman that he was going to be his tag team partner with Wippleman responding that he was scared. Wippleman also appeared as \"Handsome Harvey,\" introducing D-Generation-X on ''Raw'' on November 24, 1997. This was to make fun of [[Rick Rude]]. Rude had been a member of DX and had just left the company a week earlier to go to WCW. This resulted in Rude being on both ''Raw'' and ''WCW Monday Nitro'' on the same night. (At the time, ''Raw'' was taped every other week while ''Nitro'' was live every week).\n\nIn June 1999, after another period of absence from television broadcasts, Wippleman resurfaced on the June 13 episode of ''Sunday Night Heat'' as a referee in a match between then-Intercontinental Champion [[Jeff Jarrett]] and [[Test (wrestler)|Test]].  Test won the match after outside interference, thus being named the new champion, but he was persuaded by Jarrett's valet [[Debra Marshall|Debra]] to overturn the result and return the belt.  He also served as a [[Strikebreaker|scab]] official during the WWF referee strike in September 1999, including at the [[Unforgiven (1999)|Unforgiven]] PPV, again refereeing a match with Jarrett defending the Intercontinental title against Chyna.\n\nOn January 31, 2000, Wippleman won the WWF Women's Championship from [[Stacy Carter|The Kat]] while he was in a disguise and used the name \"Hervina\" in a \"Lumberjill Snow Bunny\" match, which took place in a snow-filled pool surrounded by female wrestlers who kept the competitors from leaving the pool.<ref name=encyclopedia/><ref name=women>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/women/304454132121112213|title=Women's Title History: Hervina|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=2009-05-06}}</ref> The win made him the first male to hold the Women's Championship.<ref name=women/> He lost the title the following day (but broadcast on February 3) to Jacqueline in a match that lasted under a minute,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/women/30445413212111216|title=Women's Title History: Jacqueline|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=2009-05-06}}</ref> thus ending the shortest reign in the title's history.  Through the remainder of 2000, Wippleman appeared in backstage and non-match segments of the WWF's television programming, including a segment on the April 23, 2000 episode of ''Sunday Night Heat'' where he appeared dressed up as a rabbit as part of a segment with [[Al Snow]] and [[Steve Blackman]].\n\nAt [[WrestleMania X-Seven]] on April 1, 2001, Wippleman managed Kamala during the gimmick battle royal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=INFC7xG77mI|title=Gimmick Battle Royal - WrestleMania X-Seven\n| publisher = YouTube |accessdate=January 17, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAt the point the [[The Invasion (professional wrestling)|Invasion storyline]] began in 2001, he had disappeared from WWF programming, and was then working as a [[List of professional wrestling terms#A|road agent]] for the company.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://morningjournal.com/articles/2008/07/27/sports/19871326.txt|title=Off the Turnbuckle: Raw-ECW merger plans have been scrapped|last=Gilles|first=Dan|newspaper=The Morning Journal|accessdate=2009-05-06|date=2008-07-27|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120218151953/http://morningjournal.com/articles/2008/07/27/sports/19871326.txt|archivedate=2012-02-18}}</ref>\n\nOn November 15, 2010, for WWE's old school episode of ''Raw'', Wippleman returned to WWE, managing the [[Brooklyn Brawler]] in a squash loss to Ezekiel Jackson.\n\nAs of 2011, Lauer was working with the WWE in backstage roles at television and pay-per-view events.  In an interview with [[Jim Korderas]], Lauer described his role as \"concierge\", taking care of details such as food, rental cars and the like.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://radio.thescore.com/episodes/harvey-whippleman-nov-10-2011|title=Harvey Whippleman - Nov 10, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20111114140835/http://radio.thescore.com/episodes/harvey-whippleman-nov-10-2011|archivedate=2011-11-14}}</ref>\n\nOn January 22, 2018, Harvey made a brief backstage appearance during [[Raw 25 Years]].\n\n==Personal life==\nLauer grew up in [[Penn Hills, Pennsylvania]], near [[Pittsburgh]].<ref name=rmn/> According to Lauer, he spent his teenage years \"sprawling on car hoods, smoking cigarettes, and drinking beer with no particular ambition in mind\".<ref name=slam/> His drinking eventually caused Lauer to serve jail time in Memphis.<ref name=slam/>\n\nIn 1994, Lauer was in a car accident with [[Joey Marella]], which claimed Marella's life and injured Lauer.<ref name=slam/> The crash occurred as a result of Marella falling asleep at the wheel while driving on the way to [[Newark, New Jersey|Newark]].<ref name=moon/> Marella was not wearing his seat belt, but Lauer\u2013the passenger\u2013was wearing his.<ref name=moon>{{cite web|url=http://www.mikemooneyham.com/pages/viewfull.cfm?ObjectID=B9F6BD0A-2627-4FE4-B3801B91D574CE58|title=Crash Claims Joey Marella|author=Mooneyham, Mike|publisher=The Wrestling Gospel|date=1994-07-10|accessdate=2009-05-07|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081113123415/http://www.mikemooneyham.com/pages/viewfull.cfm?ObjectID=B9F6BD0A-2627-4FE4-B3801B91D574CE58|archivedate=November 13, 2008}}</ref> Because of the severity of his injuries, however, Lauer incurred approximately $10,000 in medical expenses.<ref name=slam/> He wrote an autobiography ''Wrestling with the Truth'', which was released in 2008.<ref name=slam>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/Reviews/2008/08/13/6436746.html|title=Lauer's book a good glimpse at a day gone by|author=Johnson, Steven|date=August 19, 2008|accessdate=2009-05-07}}</ref><ref name=rmn/> Lauer is [[Roman Catholic]].\n\n==Championships and accomplishments==\n'''[[Continental Championship Wrestling|Continental Wrestling Federation]]'''\n*[[NWA Southeastern United States Junior Heavyweight Championship|Southeast United States Junior Heavyweight Championship]] (1 time)<ref name=\"Titles\"/>\n\n'''[[World Wrestling Entertainment|World Wrestling Federation]]'''\n*[[WWE Women's Championship (1956\u20132010)|WWF Women's Championship]] ([[List of WWE Women's Champions|1 time]])<ref name=women/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Professional wrestling profiles}}\n{{WWE Women's Championship}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wippleman, Harvey}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:American male professional wrestlers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:People from Walls, Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestling managers and valets]]\n[[Category:WWF/WWE Women's Champions]]\n", "name_user": "84.13.202.96", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harvey_Wippleman"}
